{"title_page": "Maat", "text_new": "{{short description|Egyptian deity and concepts of truth, order and justice}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{confused|Mut}}\n{{Infobox deity\n| type        = Egyptian\n| name        = Maat\n| image       = Maat.svg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Maat was both the goddess and the personification of truth and justice. Her ostrich feather represents truth.\n| god_of      = Goddess of truth, justice, wisdom, the stars, law, morality, order, harmony, the seasons, and cosmic balance\n| hiro        =<hiero>U2:Aa11-a:t:Y1</hiero>\n| cult_center = All [[ancient Egypt]]ian cities\n| symbol      = scales, [[ostrich]] feather\n| parents     = [[Ra]] and [[Hathor]]\n| siblings    = \n| consort     = [[Thoth]]\n| offspring   = [[Seshat]]\n}}\n{{Ancient Egyptian religion}}\n'''Maat''' or '''Ma\u02bdat''' (Egyptian [[wikt:m\ua723\ua725t#Egyptian|'''m\ua723\ua725t''']] /\u02c8mu\u0280\u0295at/)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6KUdBAAAQBAJ&pg=147|title=Middle Egyptian: An Introduction to the Language and Culture of Hieroglyphs|last=Allen|first=James P.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781139917094|language=en|page=147}}</ref> refers to the [[ancient Egypt]]ian concepts of [[truth]], balance, order, harmony, [[law]], [[morality]], and [[justice]]. Maat was also the goddess who personified these concepts, and regulated the stars, seasons, and the actions of mortals and the deities who had brought order from [[chaos (cosmogony)|chaos]] at the moment of creation. Her ideological opposite was [[Isfet (Egyptian mythology)|Isfet]] (Egyptian ''[[wikt:jzft|jzft]]''), meaning injustice, chaos, violence or to do evil.\n\n==Pronunciation==\nCuneiform texts indicate that the word ''m3\u02e4t'' was pronounced /m\u00fa\u0294\u0295a/ during the [[New Kingdom of Egypt]], having lost the feminine ending ''t''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gd6aAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA25|title=The Ancient Egyptian Language: An Historical Study|last=Allen|first=James P.|date=2013-07-11|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781107032460|language=en}}</ref> Vowel assimilation of ''u'' to ''e'' later produced the Coptic word {{Coptic|\u2c99\u2c89\u2c89/\u2c99\u2c89}} \"truth, justice\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://corpling.uis.georgetown.edu/coptic-dictionary/entry.cgi?entry=756&super=351|title=Coptic Dictionary Online|website=corpling.uis.georgetown.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe earliest surviving records indicating that Maat is the norm for nature and society, in this world and the next, were recorded during the [[Old Kingdom of Egypt]], the earliest substantial surviving examples being found in the [[Pyramid Texts]] of [[Unas#The Pyramid Texts|Unas]] (ca. 2375 BCE and 2345 BCE).<ref>{{cite book| author = Siegfried Morenz| title = Egyptian Religion: Siegried Morenz| year = 1973| isbn = 978-0-8014-8029-4| page = 273 }}</ref>\n\nLater, when most goddesses were paired with a male aspect, her masculine counterpart was [[Thoth]], as their attributes are similar. In other accounts, Thoth was paired off with [[Seshat]], goddess of writing and measure, who is a lesser-known deity.\n\nAfter her role in creation and continuously preventing the universe from returning to chaos, her primary role in [[ancient Egyptian religion]] dealt with the [[Weighing of the Heart]] that took place in the [[Duat]].<ref>Budge. ''The Gods of the Egyptians'' Vol. 1 p. 418.</ref> Her feather was the measure that determined whether the souls (considered to reside in the heart) of the departed would reach the paradise of the [[afterlife]] successfully.\n\n[[Pharaoh]]s are often depicted with the emblems of Maat to emphasise their role in upholding the laws and righteousness.<ref>{{cite book| author = Henrietta McCall| title = Mesopotamian myths| date = January 1990| publisher = University of Texas Press| isbn = 0-292-72076-9| page = [https://archive.org/details/egyptianmyths00hart/page/46 46]| url = https://archive.org/details/egyptianmyths00hart/page/46}}</ref>\n\n==Principle==\n[[File:Winged Maat (KV11).jpg|thumbnail|Winged Maat]]\n\nMaat represents the ethical and moral principle that every Egyptian citizen was expected to follow throughout their daily lives. They were expected to act with honor and truth in matters that involve family, the community, the nation, the environment, and the gods.<ref>{{cite book| author = Denise Martin| title = Maat and order in African Cosmology: A Conceptual Tool for Understanding Indigenous Knowledge| year =2008| page = 951}}</ref>\n\nMaat as a principle was formed to meet the complex needs of the emergent Egyptian state that embraced diverse peoples with conflicting interests.<ref name=Cohn>{{cite book| author = Norman Rufus Colin Cohn| title = Cosmos, Chaos and the World to Come: The Ancient Roots of Apocalyptic Faith| year = 1993| isbn = 978-0-300-05598-6| page = [https://archive.org/details/cosmoschaosworld00cohn/page/9 9]| url = https://archive.org/details/cosmoschaosworld00cohn/page/9}}</ref> The development of such rules sought to avert [[Civil disorder|chaos]] and it became the basis of Egyptian law. From an early period the king would describe himself as the \"Lord of Maat\" who decreed with his mouth the Maat he conceived in his heart.\n\nThe significance of Maat developed to the point that it embraced all aspects of existence, including the basic equilibrium of the universe, the relationship between constituent parts, the cycle of the seasons, heavenly movements, religious observations and fair dealings, honesty, and truthfulness in social interactions.<ref name=Cohn />\n\nThe ancient Egyptians had a deep conviction of an underlying holiness and unity within the universe. Cosmic harmony was achieved by correct public and ritual life. Any disturbance in cosmic harmony could have consequences for the individual as well as the state. An impious king could bring about famine, and blasphemy could bring blindness to an individual.<ref>[[John Romer (Egyptologist)|John Romer]], ''Testament'', pp. 41\u201342, Guild Publishing, 1988.</ref> In opposition to the right order expressed in the concept of Maat is the concept of ''Isfet'': chaos, lies and violence.<ref>''Religion and Cultural Memory: Ten Studies'', [[Jan Assmann]], Translated by Rodney Livingstone, p. 34, Stanford University Press, 2006, {{ISBN|0-8047-4523-4}}.</ref>\n\nIn addition to the importance of the Maat, several other principles within ancient Egyptian law were essential, including an adherence to tradition as opposed to change, the importance of rhetorical skill, and the significance of achieving impartiality and \"righteous action\". In one [[Middle Kingdom of Egypt|Middle Kingdom]] (2062 to c.1664 BCE) text, the creator declares \"''I made every man like his fellow''\". Maat called the rich to help the less fortunate rather than exploit them, echoed in tomb declarations: \"''I have given bread to the hungry and clothed the naked''\" and \"''I was a husband to the widow and father to the orphan''\".<ref>{{cite book| author = James P. Allen| title = Middle Egyptian: An Introduction to the Language and Culture of Hieroglyphs| year = 2000| isbn = 978-0-521-77483-3| page = 116 }}</ref>\n\nTo the Egyptian mind, Maat bound all things together in an indestructible unity: the universe, the natural world, the state, and the individual were all seen as parts of the wider order generated by Maat.\n\nA passage in the Instruction of [[Ptahhotep]] presents Maat as follows:\n\n:''Maat is good and its worth is lasting.''\n:''It has not been disturbed since the day of its creator,'' \n:''whereas he who transgresses its ordinances is punished.''\n:''It lies as a path in front even of him who knows nothing.''\n:''Wrongdoing has never yet brought its venture to port.''\n:''It is true that evil may gain wealth but the strength of truth is that it lasts;''\n:''a man can say: \"It was the property of my father.\"''<ref>{{cite book |last=Frankfort |first=Henri |title=Ancient Egyptian Religion |page=62}}</ref>\n\n===Law===\n[[Image:maat.jpg|thumb|Maat wearing feather of truth]]\n\nThere is little surviving literature that describes the practice of ancient Egyptian law. Maat was the spirit in which justice was applied rather than the detailed legalistic exposition of rules. Maat represented the normal and basic values that formed the backdrop for the application of justice that had to be carried out in the spirit of truth and fairness. From the [[Fifth Dynasty of Egypt|Fifth Dynasty]] (c. 2510\u20132370 BCE) onwards, the [[vizier]] responsible for justice was called the ''Priest of Maat'' and in later periods judges wore images of Maat.<ref>{{cite book| author = Siegfried Morenz| title = Egyptian Religion: Siegried Morenz| year = 1973| isbn = 978-0-8014-8029-4| pages = 117\u2013125 }}</ref>\n\nLater scholars and philosophers also would embody concepts from the [[Sebayt]], a native [[wisdom literature]]. These spiritual texts dealt with common social or professional situations, and how each was best to be resolved or addressed in the spirit of Maat. It was very practical advice, and highly case-based, so few specific and general rules could be derived from them.<ref>{{cite book| author = Roland Murphy| title = The Interpretation of Old Testament Wisdom Literature| year = 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Ptolemaic Kingdom|Greek period in Egyptian history]], Greek law existed alongside Egyptian law. The Egyptian law preserved the rights of women, who were allowed to act independently of men and own substantial personal property, and in time, this influenced the more restrictive conventions of the Greeks and Romans.<ref>{{cite book| author = Anton Powell| title = The Greek World| year = 1995| publisher = Psychology Press| isbn = 978-0-415-17042-0| page = 303 }}</ref> When the Romans took control of Egypt, the Roman legal system, which existed throughout the Roman Empire, was imposed in Egypt.\n\n===Scribes===\nScribes held prestigious positions in ancient Egyptian society in view of their importance in the transmission of religious, political, and commercial information.<ref>Black, p. 130</ref>\n\nThoth was the patron of scribes who is described as the one \"who reveals Maat and reckons Maat; who loves Maat and gives Maat to the doer of Maat\".<ref>Black, p. 131</ref> In texts such as the [[Instruction of Amenemope]] the scribe is urged to follow the precepts of Maat in his private life as well as his work.<ref>Black, p. 132</ref> The exhortations to live according to Maat are such that these kinds of instructional texts have been described as \"Maat Literature\".<ref>Black, p. 157</ref>\n\n==Goddess==\n{{Hiero|Goddess Maat<ref>Hieroglyphs can be found in (Collier and Manley pp. 27, 29, 154)</ref><ref name=Budge416>Budge ''The Gods of the Egyptians'' Vol. 1 p. 416</ref>|<hiero>U5:a-t-C10 ! or H6 ! or U5:D36-X1-Y1:Z1*Z1*Z1*Z1 ! or U1-Aa11:X1-C10 ! or C10 ! or U5:D42-X1:Y1:Z2-I12 ! or U5:D42:X1-H6-C10-Y1-Z3 ! or H6-X1:H8-C10 </hiero>|align=right|era=egypt}}\n\nMaat was the goddess of harmony, justice, and truth represented as a young woman.<ref>{{cite book| author = Robert A. Armour| title = Gods and Myths of Ancient Egypt| year = 2001| publisher = American University in Cairo Press| isbn = 978-977-424-669-2 }}</ref> Sometimes she is depicted with wings on each arm or as a woman with an ostrich feather on her head.<ref name=Budge416/> The meaning of this emblem is uncertain, although the god [[Shu (Egyptian deity)|Shu]], who in some myths is Maat's brother, also wears it.<ref name=\"Vol p. 320\">\"The Oxford Encyclopedia of Ancient Egypt\" Vol. 2 p. 320</ref> Depictions of Maat as a goddess are recorded from as early as the middle of the [[Old Kingdom]] (c. 2680 to 2190 BCE).<ref>''The Oxford Essential Guide to Egyptian Mythology'', Edited by [[Donald B. Redford]], p. 190, Berkeley, 2003, {{ISBN|0-425-19096-X}}</ref>\n\nThe sun-god [[Ra]] came from the primaeval mound of creation only after he set his daughter Maat in place of Isfet (chaos). Kings inherited the duty to ensure Maat remained in place, and they with Ra are said to \"live on Maat\", with [[Akhenaten]] (r. 1372\u20131355 BCE) in particular emphasising the concept to a degree that the king's contemporaries viewed as intolerance and fanaticism.<ref>Ray, John D. ''Reflections on Osiris'', p. 64, Profile books, 2002, {{ISBN|186197 490 6}}; An inscription of [[Hatshepsut]] reads ''\"I have made bright the truth which he [Amun-Re] loved, [I] know that he liveth by it the truth[Maat]; it is my bread, I eat of its brightness\"'' (Breasted Records, V2, p. 123)</ref> Some kings incorporated Maat into their names, being referred to as ''Lords of Maat'',<ref>{{cite book| author = [[Barry J. Kemp]]| title = 100 hieroglyphs: think like an Egyptian| year = 2005| isbn = 1-86207-658-8 }}</ref> or ''Meri-Maat'' (''Beloved of Maat'').<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:maat3.jpg|thumb|right|Maat with outstretched wings]] -->\n\nMaat had an invaluable role in the ceremony of the Weighing of the Heart. \n\n===Temples===\nThe earliest evidence for a dedicated temple is in the [[New Kingdom]] (c. 1569 to 1081 BCE) era, despite the great importance placed on Maat. [[Amenhotep III]] commissioned a temple in the [[Karnak]] complex, whilst textual evidence indicates that other temples of Maat were located in [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] and at [[Deir el-Medina]].<ref>''The Essential Guide to Egyptian Mythology: The Oxford Guide'', p. 190, Berkeley Reference, 2003, {{ISBN|0-425-19096-X}}</ref> The Maat temple at the Karnak complex was also used by courts to meet regarding the robberies of the royal tombs during the rule of [[Ramesses IX]].<ref name=\"Vol p. 320\"/>\n\n==Afterlife==\n{{See also|Maat Kheru|l1=True of Voice}}\n\n===Weighing of the Heart===\nIn the [[Duat]], the Egyptian [[underworld]], the hearts of the dead were said to be weighed against her single \"Feather of Maat\", symbolically representing the concept of Maat, in the ''Hall of Two Truths''. This is why hearts were left in Egyptian mummies while their other organs were removed, as the heart (called \"ib\") was seen as part of the [[Egyptian soul]]. If the heart was found to be lighter or equal in weight to the feather of Maat, the deceased had led a virtuous life and would go on to [[Aaru]]. [[Osiris]] came to be seen as the guardian of the gates of Aaru after he became part of the Egyptian pantheon and displaced [[Anubis]] in the [[Ogdoad (Egyptian)|Ogdoad tradition]]. A heart which was unworthy was devoured by the goddess [[Ammit]] and its owner condemned to remain in the Duat.<ref name=Weighing>{{cite web |url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/young_explorers/discover/museum_explorer/ancient_egypt/death/weighing_the_heart.aspx |title= Death in Ancient Egypt: Weighing the Heart |website= British Museum |publisher= British Museum |accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe weighing of the heart, pictured on [[papyrus]] in the [[Book of the Dead]] typically, or in tomb scenes, shows Anubis overseeing the weighing and Ammit seated awaiting the results so she could consume those who failed. The image would be the vertical heart on one flat surface of the ''balance scale'' and the vertical Shu-feather standing on the other balance scale surface.  Other traditions hold that Anubis brought the soul before the posthumous Osiris who performed the weighing. While the heart was weighed the deceased recited the 42 Negative Confessions as the [[Assessors of Maat]] looked on.<ref name=Weighing/>\n\n===Funerary texts===\n[[File:Egypt dauingevekten.jpg|thumb|A section of the ''[[Book of the Dead]]'' showing the [[Weighing of the Heart]] in the [[Duat]] using the feather of Maat as the measure in balance]]\n\nEgyptians were often entombed with funerary texts in order to be well equipped for the afterlife as mandated by [[ancient Egyptian funerary practices]]. These often served to guide the deceased through the afterlife, and the most famous one is the ''Book of the Dead'' or ''[[Papyrus of Ani]]'' (known to the ancient Egyptians as ''The Book of Coming Forth by Day''). The lines of these texts are often collectively called the \"Forty-Two Declarations of Purity\".<ref name=Ani>{{cite web| url= https://www.africa.upenn.edu/Books/Papyrus_Ani.html|title= The Papyrus of Ani}}</ref> These declarations varied somewhat from tomb to tomb as they were tailored to the individual, and so cannot be considered a canonical definition of Maat. Rather, they appear to express each tomb owner's individual practices in life to please Maat, as well as words of absolution from misdeeds or mistakes, made by the tomb owner in life, which could be declared as not having been done, and through the power of the written word, wipe particular misdeed from the afterlife record of the deceased. Many of the lines are similar, however, and paint a very unified picture of Maat.<ref name=Ani/>\n\nThe doctrine of Maat is represented in the declarations to Rekhti-merti-f-ent-Maat and the 42 Negative Confessions listed in the ''Papyrus of Ani''. The following are translations by [[E. A. Wallis Budge]].<ref name=Ani/>\n{{Anchor|confessions}}\n\n===42 Negative Confessions (''Papyrus of Ani'')<!--linked from 'Papyrus of Ani'-->===\nFrom the ''[[Papyrus of Ani]]''.\n{{div col}}\n# I have not committed sin.\n# I have not committed robbery with violence.\n# I have not stolen.\n# I have not slain men and women.\n# I have not stolen grain.\n# I have not purloined offerings.\n# I have not stolen the property of the gods.\n# I have not uttered lies.\n# I have not carried away food.\n# I have not uttered curses.\n# I have not committed adultery.\n# I have made none to weep.\n# I have not eaten the heart [i.e., I have not grieved uselessly, or felt remorse].\n# I have not attacked any man.\n# I am not a man of deceit.\n# I have not stolen cultivated land.\n# I have not been an eavesdropper.\n# I have slandered no man.\n# I have not been angry without just cause.\n# I have not debauched the wife of any man.\n# I have not debauched the wife of any man (repeats the previous affirmation but addressed to a different god).\n# I have not polluted myself.\n# I have terrorized none.\n# I have not transgressed the Law.\n# I have not been wroth.\n# I have not shut my ears to the words of truth.\n# I have not blasphemed.\n# I am not a man of violence.\n# I am not a stirrer up of strife (or a disturber of the peace).\n# I have not acted (or judged) with undue haste.\n# I have not pried into matters.\n# I have not multiplied my words in speaking.\n# I have wronged none, I have done no evil.\n# I have not worked witchcraft against the King (or blasphemed against the King).\n# I have never stopped the flow of water.\n# I have never raised my voice (spoken arrogantly, or in anger).\n# I have not cursed or blasphemed God.\n# I have not acted with evil rage.\n# I have not stolen the bread of the gods.\n# I have not carried away the khenfu cakes from the spirits of the dead.\n# I have not snatched away the bread of the child, nor treated with contempt the god of my city.\n# I have not slain the cattle belonging to the god.<ref>{{cite book| title = The Book of the Dead| date = 1995-01-23| publisher = Gramercy| isbn = 978-0-517-12283-9| pages = 576\u2013582 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Sir Ernest Alfred Wallis Budge|authorlink=E. A. Wallis Budge|title=The Papyrus of Ani: A Reproduction in Facsimile, Edited, with Hieroglyphic Transcript, Translation, and Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA576|year=1913|publisher=Medici Society|pages=576\u2013582|quote=Image of [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA576&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U30DEywqNadiJv2SJKZOFyV-Qd5_g&ci=150%2C660%2C800%2C596&edge=0 p.&nbsp;576] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA577&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U2JFJlW2Meg9p431udj7PoIr8R3Nw&ci=63%2C159%2C769%2C1204&edge=0 p.&nbsp;577] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA578&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U1Jdr9ualNT85zBejA5gaNzWyhu_g&ci=145%2C153%2C850%2C1218&edge=0 p.&nbsp;578] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA579&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U2Rk6I2S3WZ-VvXhBVX3v3oCyx-pA&ci=30%2C177%2C820%2C1222&edge=0 p.&nbsp;579] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA580&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U1PmV9f9FK7qNm4lRHELMx1r21J0w&ci=160%2C155%2C820%2C1207&edge=0 p.&nbsp;580] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA581&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U2GZFEn330Ow6TUcwCANdbjK6R7Zw&ci=37%2C168%2C810%2C1212&edge=0 p.&nbsp;581] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA582&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U1b3Y5ZqALeLzM2O3ysYLq07Qh-pQ&ci=160%2C169%2C800%2C664&edge=0 p.&nbsp;582] at Google Books}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Assessors of Maat====\n{{Further|Assessors of Maat}}\nThe [[Assessors of Maat]] are the 42 deities listed in the ''Papyrus of Nebseni'',<ref name=\"Nebseni\">{{cite web|url=https://www.touregypt.net/bod123.htm|title=Papyrus of Nebseni|accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> to whom the deceased make the Negative Confession in the ''[[Papyrus of Ani]]''.<ref>Budge ''The Gods of the Egyptians'' Vol. 1 pp. 418\u201320</ref> They represent the 42 united [[Nome (Egypt)|nomes]] of Egypt, and are called \"the hidden Maati gods, who feed upon Maat during the years of their lives;\" i.e., they are the righteous minor deities who deserve offerings.<ref name=\"Ani\" /> As the deceased follows the set formula of Negative Confessions, he addresses each god directly and mentions the nome of which the god is a patron, in order to emphasize the unity of the nomes of Egypt.<ref name=\"Nebseni\" />\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"190\" heights=\"154\">\nFile:Offering maat.JPG|Statuette of a kneeling man, maybe a priest, offering a small Maat figure. Bronze with agemina. [[Third Intermediate Period]]/[[Late Period of ancient Egypt|Late Period]]\nFile:Deir el-Medina 2016-03-23j.jpg|Ancient artisans\u2019 village [[Deir el-Medina]] in [[Upper Egypt]]\nFile:Edfu22.JPG|[[Relief]] of Maat in east upstairs. [[Temple of Edfu]], Upper Egypt\nFile:Flickr - archer10 (Dennis) - Egypt-5A-044.jpg|Depiction of the Feast of the Beautiful Meeting, the second reunion between [[Horus]] and his wife [[Hathor]]. Temple of Edfu, Upper Egypt\nFile:RamessesIX-OstraconPresentingMaat MetropolitanMuseum.png|[[Ostracon]] depicting the pharaoh [[Ramesses IX]] presenting Maat\nFile:Temple of Deir el-Medina 13.JPG|Relief in the inner room of Hathor's temple in Deir el-Medina\nFile:Osiris E9418 mp3h8805.jpg|Maat represented with wings\n\nFile:\u0411\u0430\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0444 \u0441 \u0438\u0437\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u0435\u0433\u0438\u043f\u0442\u044f\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0441\u043e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0443\u044d\u0442\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u041c\u0430\u0430\u0442.jpg|[[Bas-relief]] depicting the Egyptian statuette of Maat. [[Old Kingdom]] \n</gallery>\n\n{{Portal|Traditional African religion}}\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Black, James Roger. ''[https://archive.is/20140430002426/https://www.shemtaia.com/diss.shtml The Instruction of Amenemope: A Critical Edition and Commentary&nbsp;\u2013 Prolegomenon and Prologue]'', Dissertation University of Wisconsin-Madison, 2002\n* [[E. A. Wallis Budge|Budge, E. A. Wallis]]. ''The Egyptian Book of the Dead: (The Papyrus of Ani) Egyptian Text Transliteration and Translation''. New York: Dover Publications, 1967. Originally published in 1895.\n* Budge, E. A. Wallis. ''The Gods of the Egyptians: Studies in Egyptian Mythology&nbsp;\u2013 Volume 1''. New York: Dover Publications, 1969. Originally published in 1904.\n* Collier, Mark and Manly, Bill. ''[[How to Read Egyptian Hieroglyphs]]: Revised Edition''. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1998.\n* Faulkner, Raymond. ''The Egyptian Book of the Dead''. San Francisco: Chronicle Books, 1994. {{ISBN|0-8118-6489-8}}\n* Mancini, Anna. ''Maat Revealed: Philosophy of Justice in Ancient Egypt''. New York: Buenos Books America, 2004.\n* Strudwick, Helen. (2006). ''The Encyclopedia of Ancient Egypt''. Singapore: De Agostini UK.\n* ''Journey through the afterlife, Ancient Egyptian Book of the Dead'' edited by John H. Taylor ([[the British Museum Press]] 2010. London {{ISBN|0-7141-1989-X}})\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Jan Assmann|Assmann, Jan]] (1990). ''Ma\u02bdat: Gerechtigkeit und Unsterblichkeit im Alten \u00c4gypten'' (in German). C.H. Beck Verlag. {{ISBN|3406346677}}.\n* Menu, Bernadette (2005). ''Ma\u00e2t: L'ordre juste du monde'' (in French). Editions Michalon. {{ISBN|2841862836}}.\n\n{{Ancient Egyptian religion footer|collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Egyptian goddesses]]\n[[Category:Justice goddesses]]\n[[Category:Ancient Near East law]]\n[[Category:Ancient Egyptian concepts]]\n[[Category:Book of the Dead]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Egyptian deity and concepts of truth, order and justice}}\n{{other uses2|Maat}}\n{{confused|Mut}}\n{{Infobox deity\n| type        = Egyptian\n| name        = Maat\n| image       = Maat.svg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Maat was both the goddess and the personification of truth and justice. Her ostrich feather represents truth.\n| god_of      = Goddess of truth, justice, wisdom, the stars, law, morality, order, harmony, the seasons, and cosmic balance\n| hiro        =<hiero>U2:Aa11-a:t:Y1</hiero>\n| cult_center = All [[ancient Egypt]]ian cities\n| symbol      = scales, [[ostrich]] feather\n| parents     = [[Ra]] and [[Hathor]]\n| siblings    = \n| consort     = [[Thoth]]\n| offspring   = [[Seshat]]\n}}\n{{Ancient Egyptian religion}}\n'''Maat''' or '''Ma\u02bdat''' (Egyptian [[wikt:m\ua723\ua725t#Egyptian|'''m\ua723\ua725t''']] /\u02c8mu\u0280\u0295at/)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6KUdBAAAQBAJ&pg=147|title=Middle Egyptian: An Introduction to the Language and Culture of Hieroglyphs|last=Allen|first=James P.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781139917094|language=en|page=147}}</ref> refers to the [[ancient Egypt]]ian concepts of [[truth]], balance, order, harmony, [[law]], [[morality]], and [[justice]]. Maat was also the goddess who personified these concepts, and regulated the stars, seasons, and the actions of mortals and the deities who had brought order from [[chaos (cosmogony)|chaos]] at the moment of creation. Her ideological opposite was [[Isfet (Egyptian mythology)|Isfet]] (Egyptian ''[[wikt:jzft|jzft]]''), meaning injustice, chaos, violence or to do evil.\n\n==Pronunciation==\nCuneiform texts indicate that the word ''m3\u02e4t'' was pronounced /m\u00fa\u0294\u0295a/ during the [[New Kingdom of Egypt]], having lost the feminine ending ''t''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gd6aAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA25|title=The Ancient Egyptian Language: An Historical Study|last=Allen|first=James P.|date=2013-07-11|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781107032460|language=en}}</ref> Vowel assimilation of ''u'' to ''e'' later produced the Coptic word {{Coptic|\u2c99\u2c89\u2c89/\u2c99\u2c89}} \"truth, justice\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://corpling.uis.georgetown.edu/coptic-dictionary/entry.cgi?entry=756&super=351|title=Coptic Dictionary Online|website=corpling.uis.georgetown.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe earliest surviving records indicating that Maat is the norm for nature and society, in this world and the next, were recorded during the [[Old Kingdom of Egypt]], the earliest substantial surviving examples being found in the [[Pyramid Texts]] of [[Unas#The Pyramid Texts|Unas]] (ca. 2375 BCE and 2345 BCE).<ref>{{cite book| author = Siegfried Morenz| title = Egyptian Religion: Siegried Morenz| year = 1973| isbn = 978-0-8014-8029-4| page = 273 }}</ref>\n\nLater, when most goddesses were paired with a male aspect, her masculine counterpart was [[Thoth]], as their attributes are similar. In other accounts, Thoth was paired off with [[Seshat]], goddess of writing and measure, who is a lesser-known deity.\n\nAfter her role in creation and continuously preventing the universe from returning to chaos, her primary role in [[ancient Egyptian religion]] dealt with the [[Weighing of the Heart]] that took place in the [[Duat]].<ref>Budge. ''The Gods of the Egyptians'' Vol. 1 p. 418.</ref> Her feather was the measure that determined whether the souls (considered to reside in the heart) of the departed would reach the paradise of the [[afterlife]] successfully.\n\n[[Pharaoh]]s are often depicted with the emblems of Maat to emphasise their role in upholding the laws and righteousness.<ref>{{cite book| author = Henrietta McCall| title = Mesopotamian myths| date = January 1990| publisher = University of Texas Press| isbn = 0-292-72076-9| page = [https://archive.org/details/egyptianmyths00hart/page/46 46]| url = https://archive.org/details/egyptianmyths00hart/page/46}}</ref>\n\n==Principle==\n[[File:Winged Maat (KV11).jpg|thumbnail|Winged Maat]]\n\nMaat represents the ethical and moral principle that every Egyptian citizen was expected to follow throughout their daily lives. They were expected to act with honor and truth in matters that involve family, the community, the nation, the environment, and the gods.<ref>{{cite book| author = Denise Martin| title = Maat and order in African Cosmology: A Conceptual Tool for Understanding Indigenous Knowledge| year =2008| page = 951}}</ref>\n\nMaat as a principle was formed to meet the complex needs of the emergent Egyptian state that embraced diverse peoples with conflicting interests.<ref name=Cohn>{{cite book| author = Norman Rufus Colin Cohn| title = Cosmos, Chaos and the World to Come: The Ancient Roots of Apocalyptic Faith| year = 1993| isbn = 978-0-300-05598-6| page = [https://archive.org/details/cosmoschaosworld00cohn/page/9 9]| url = https://archive.org/details/cosmoschaosworld00cohn/page/9}}</ref> The development of such rules sought to avert [[Civil disorder|chaos]] and it became the basis of Egyptian law. From an early period the king would describe himself as the \"Lord of Maat\" who decreed with his mouth the Maat he conceived in his heart.\n\nThe significance of Maat developed to the point that it embraced all aspects of existence, including the basic equilibrium of the universe, the relationship between constituent parts, the cycle of the seasons, heavenly movements, religious observations and fair dealings, honesty, and truthfulness in social interactions.<ref name=Cohn />\n\nThe ancient Egyptians had a deep conviction of an underlying holiness and unity within the universe. Cosmic harmony was achieved by correct public and ritual life. Any disturbance in cosmic harmony could have consequences for the individual as well as the state. An impious king could bring about famine, and blasphemy could bring blindness to an individual.<ref>[[John Romer (Egyptologist)|John Romer]], ''Testament'', pp. 41\u201342, Guild Publishing, 1988.</ref> In opposition to the right order expressed in the concept of Maat is the concept of ''Isfet'': chaos, lies and violence.<ref>''Religion and Cultural Memory: Ten Studies'', [[Jan Assmann]], Translated by Rodney Livingstone, p. 34, Stanford University Press, 2006, {{ISBN|0-8047-4523-4}}.</ref>\n\nIn addition to the importance of the Maat, several other principles within ancient Egyptian law were essential, including an adherence to tradition as opposed to change, the importance of rhetorical skill, and the significance of achieving impartiality and \"righteous action\". In one [[Middle Kingdom of Egypt|Middle Kingdom]] (2062 to c.1664 BCE) text, the creator declares \"''I made every man like his fellow''\". Maat called the rich to help the less fortunate rather than exploit them, echoed in tomb declarations: \"''I have given bread to the hungry and clothed the naked''\" and \"''I was a husband to the widow and father to the orphan''\".<ref>{{cite book| author = James P. Allen| title = Middle Egyptian: An Introduction to the Language and Culture of Hieroglyphs| year = 2000| isbn = 978-0-521-77483-3| page = 116 }}</ref>\n\nTo the Egyptian mind, Maat bound all things together in an indestructible unity: the universe, the natural world, the state, and the individual were all seen as parts of the wider order generated by Maat.\n\nA passage in the Instruction of [[Ptahhotep]] presents Maat as follows:\n\n:''Maat is good and its worth is lasting.''\n:''It has not been disturbed since the day of its creator,'' \n:''whereas he who transgresses its ordinances is punished.''\n:''It lies as a path in front even of him who knows nothing.''\n:''Wrongdoing has never yet brought its venture to port.''\n:''It is true that evil may gain wealth but the strength of truth is that it lasts;''\n:''a man can say: \"It was the property of my father.\"''<ref>{{cite book |last=Frankfort |first=Henri |title=Ancient Egyptian Religion |page=62}}</ref>\n\n===Law===\n[[Image:maat.jpg|thumb|Maat wearing feather of truth]]\n\nThere is little surviving literature that describes the practice of ancient Egyptian law. Maat was the spirit in which justice was applied rather than the detailed legalistic exposition of rules. Maat represented the normal and basic values that formed the backdrop for the application of justice that had to be carried out in the spirit of truth and fairness. From the [[Fifth Dynasty of Egypt|Fifth Dynasty]] (c. 2510\u20132370 BCE) onwards, the [[vizier]] responsible for justice was called the ''Priest of Maat'' and in later periods judges wore images of Maat.<ref>{{cite book| author = Siegfried Morenz| title = Egyptian Religion: Siegried Morenz| year = 1973| isbn = 978-0-8014-8029-4| pages = 117\u2013125 }}</ref>\n\nLater scholars and philosophers also would embody concepts from the [[Sebayt]], a native [[wisdom literature]]. These spiritual texts dealt with common social or professional situations, and how each was best to be resolved or addressed in the spirit of Maat. It was very practical advice, and highly case-based, so few specific and general rules could be derived from them.<ref>{{cite book| author = Roland Murphy| title = The Interpretation of Old Testament Wisdom Literature| year = 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Ptolemaic Kingdom|Greek period in Egyptian history]], Greek law existed alongside Egyptian law. The Egyptian law preserved the rights of women, who were allowed to act independently of men and own substantial personal property, and in time, this influenced the more restrictive conventions of the Greeks and Romans.<ref>{{cite book| author = Anton Powell| title = The Greek World| year = 1995| publisher = Psychology Press| isbn = 978-0-415-17042-0| page = 303 }}</ref> When the Romans took control of Egypt, the Roman legal system, which existed throughout the Roman Empire, was imposed in Egypt.\n\n===Scribes===\nScribes held prestigious positions in ancient Egyptian society in view of their importance in the transmission of religious, political, and commercial information.<ref>Black, p. 130</ref>\n\nThoth was the patron of scribes who is described as the one \"who reveals Maat and reckons Maat; who loves Maat and gives Maat to the doer of Maat\".<ref>Black, p. 131</ref> In texts such as the [[Instruction of Amenemope]] the scribe is urged to follow the precepts of Maat in his private life as well as his work.<ref>Black, p. 132</ref> The exhortations to live according to Maat are such that these kinds of instructional texts have been described as \"Maat Literature\".<ref>Black, p. 157</ref>\n\n==Goddess==\n{{Hiero|Goddess Maat<ref>Hieroglyphs can be found in (Collier and Manley pp. 27, 29, 154)</ref><ref name=Budge416>Budge ''The Gods of the Egyptians'' Vol. 1 p. 416</ref>|<hiero>U5:a-t-C10 ! or H6 ! or U5:D36-X1-Y1:Z1*Z1*Z1*Z1 ! or U1-Aa11:X1-C10 ! or C10 ! or U5:D42-X1:Y1:Z2-I12 ! or U5:D42:X1-H6-C10-Y1-Z3 ! or H6-X1:H8-C10 </hiero>|align=right|era=egypt}}\n\nMaat was the goddess of harmony, justice, and truth represented as a young woman.<ref>{{cite book| author = Robert A. Armour| title = Gods and Myths of Ancient Egypt| year = 2001| publisher = American University in Cairo Press| isbn = 978-977-424-669-2 }}</ref> Sometimes she is depicted with wings on each arm or as a woman with an ostrich feather on her head.<ref name=Budge416/> The meaning of this emblem is uncertain, although the god [[Shu (Egyptian deity)|Shu]], who in some myths is Maat's brother, also wears it.<ref name=\"Vol p. 320\">\"The Oxford Encyclopedia of Ancient Egypt\" Vol. 2 p. 320</ref> Depictions of Maat as a goddess are recorded from as early as the middle of the [[Old Kingdom]] (c. 2680 to 2190 BCE).<ref>''The Oxford Essential Guide to Egyptian Mythology'', Edited by [[Donald B. Redford]], p. 190, Berkeley, 2003, {{ISBN|0-425-19096-X}}</ref>\n\nThe sun-god [[Ra]] came from the primaeval mound of creation only after he set his daughter Maat in place of Isfet (chaos). Kings inherited the duty to ensure Maat remained in place, and they with Ra are said to \"live on Maat\", with [[Akhenaten]] (r. 1372\u20131355 BCE) in particular emphasising the concept to a degree that the king's contemporaries viewed as intolerance and fanaticism.<ref>Ray, John D. ''Reflections on Osiris'', p. 64, Profile books, 2002, {{ISBN|186197 490 6}}; An inscription of [[Hatshepsut]] reads ''\"I have made bright the truth which he [Amun-Re] loved, [I] know that he liveth by it the truth[Maat]; it is my bread, I eat of its brightness\"'' (Breasted Records, V2, p. 123)</ref> Some kings incorporated Maat into their names, being referred to as ''Lords of Maat'',<ref>{{cite book| author = [[Barry J. Kemp]]| title = 100 hieroglyphs: think like an Egyptian| year = 2005| isbn = 1-86207-658-8 }}</ref> or ''Meri-Maat'' (''Beloved of Maat'').<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:maat3.jpg|thumb|right|Maat with outstretched wings]] -->\n\nMaat had an invaluable role in the ceremony of the Weighing of the Heart. \n\n===Temples===\nThe earliest evidence for a dedicated temple is in the [[New Kingdom]] (c. 1569 to 1081 BCE) era, despite the great importance placed on Maat. [[Amenhotep III]] commissioned a temple in the [[Karnak]] complex, whilst textual evidence indicates that other temples of Maat were located in [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] and at [[Deir el-Medina]].<ref>''The Essential Guide to Egyptian Mythology: The Oxford Guide'', p. 190, Berkeley Reference, 2003, {{ISBN|0-425-19096-X}}</ref> The Maat temple at the Karnak complex was also used by courts to meet regarding the robberies of the royal tombs during the rule of [[Ramesses IX]].<ref name=\"Vol p. 320\"/>\n\n==Afterlife==\n{{See also|Maat Kheru|l1=True of Voice}}\n\n===Weighing of the Heart===\nIn the [[Duat]], the Egyptian [[underworld]], the hearts of the dead were said to be weighed against her single \"Feather of Maat\", symbolically representing the concept of Maat, in the ''Hall of Two Truths''. This is why hearts were left in Egyptian mummies while their other organs were removed, as the heart (called \"ib\") was seen as part of the [[Egyptian soul]]. If the heart was found to be lighter or equal in weight to the feather of Maat, the deceased had led a virtuous life and would go on to [[Aaru]]. [[Osiris]] came to be seen as the guardian of the gates of Aaru after he became part of the Egyptian pantheon and displaced [[Anubis]] in the [[Ogdoad (Egyptian)|Ogdoad tradition]]. A heart which was unworthy was devoured by the goddess [[Ammit]] and its owner condemned to remain in the Duat.<ref name=Weighing>{{cite web |url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/young_explorers/discover/museum_explorer/ancient_egypt/death/weighing_the_heart.aspx |title= Death in Ancient Egypt: Weighing the Heart |website= British Museum |publisher= British Museum |accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe weighing of the heart, pictured on [[papyrus]] in the [[Book of the Dead]] typically, or in tomb scenes, shows Anubis overseeing the weighing and Ammit seated awaiting the results so she could consume those who failed. The image would be the vertical heart on one flat surface of the ''balance scale'' and the vertical Shu-feather standing on the other balance scale surface.  Other traditions hold that Anubis brought the soul before the posthumous Osiris who performed the weighing. While the heart was weighed the deceased recited the 42 Negative Confessions as the [[Assessors of Maat]] looked on.<ref name=Weighing/>\n\n===Funerary texts===\n[[File:Egypt dauingevekten.jpg|thumb|A section of the ''[[Book of the Dead]]'' showing the [[Weighing of the Heart]] in the [[Duat]] using the feather of Maat as the measure in balance]]\n\nEgyptians were often entombed with funerary texts in order to be well equipped for the afterlife as mandated by [[ancient Egyptian funerary practices]]. These often served to guide the deceased through the afterlife, and the most famous one is the ''Book of the Dead'' or ''[[Papyrus of Ani]]'' (known to the ancient Egyptians as ''The Book of Coming Forth by Day''). The lines of these texts are often collectively called the \"Forty-Two Declarations of Purity\".<ref name=Ani>{{cite web| url= https://www.africa.upenn.edu/Books/Papyrus_Ani.html|title= The Papyrus of Ani}}</ref> These declarations varied somewhat from tomb to tomb as they were tailored to the individual, and so cannot be considered a canonical definition of Maat. Rather, they appear to express each tomb owner's individual practices in life to please Maat, as well as words of absolution from misdeeds or mistakes, made by the tomb owner in life, which could be declared as not having been done, and through the power of the written word, wipe particular misdeed from the afterlife record of the deceased. Many of the lines are similar, however, and paint a very unified picture of Maat.<ref name=Ani/>\n\nThe doctrine of Maat is represented in the declarations to Rekhti-merti-f-ent-Maat and the 42 Negative Confessions listed in the ''Papyrus of Ani''. The following are translations by [[E. A. Wallis Budge]].<ref name=Ani/>\n{{Anchor|confessions}}\n\n===42 Negative Confessions (''Papyrus of Ani'')<!--linked from 'Papyrus of Ani'-->===\nFrom the ''[[Papyrus of Ani]]''.\n{{div col}}\n# I have not committed sin.\n# I have not committed robbery with violence.\n# I have not stolen.\n# I have not slain men and women.\n# I have not stolen grain.\n# I have not purloined offerings.\n# I have not stolen the property of the gods.\n# I have not uttered lies.\n# I have not carried away food.\n# I have not uttered curses.\n# I have not committed adultery.\n# I have made none to weep.\n# I have not eaten the heart [i.e., I have not grieved uselessly, or felt remorse].\n# I have not attacked any man.\n# I am not a man of deceit.\n# I have not stolen cultivated land.\n# I have not been an eavesdropper.\n# I have slandered no man.\n# I have not been angry without just cause.\n# I have not debauched the wife of any man.\n# I have not debauched the wife of any man (repeats the previous affirmation but addressed to a different god).\n# I have not polluted myself.\n# I have terrorized none.\n# I have not transgressed the Law.\n# I have not been wroth.\n# I have not shut my ears to the words of truth.\n# I have not blasphemed.\n# I am not a man of violence.\n# I am not a stirrer up of strife (or a disturber of the peace).\n# I have not acted (or judged) with undue haste.\n# I have not pried into matters.\n# I have not multiplied my words in speaking.\n# I have wronged none, I have done no evil.\n# I have not worked witchcraft against the King (or blasphemed against the King).\n# I have never stopped the flow of water.\n# I have never raised my voice (spoken arrogantly, or in anger).\n# I have not cursed or blasphemed God.\n# I have not acted with evil rage.\n# I have not stolen the bread of the gods.\n# I have not carried away the khenfu cakes from the spirits of the dead.\n# I have not snatched away the bread of the child, nor treated with contempt the god of my city.\n# I have not slain the cattle belonging to the god.<ref>{{cite book| title = The Book of the Dead| date = 1995-01-23| publisher = Gramercy| isbn = 978-0-517-12283-9| pages = 576\u2013582 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Sir Ernest Alfred Wallis Budge|authorlink=E. A. Wallis Budge|title=The Papyrus of Ani: A Reproduction in Facsimile, Edited, with Hieroglyphic Transcript, Translation, and Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA576|year=1913|publisher=Medici Society|pages=576\u2013582|quote=Image of [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA576&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U30DEywqNadiJv2SJKZOFyV-Qd5_g&ci=150%2C660%2C800%2C596&edge=0 p.&nbsp;576] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA577&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U2JFJlW2Meg9p431udj7PoIr8R3Nw&ci=63%2C159%2C769%2C1204&edge=0 p.&nbsp;577] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA578&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U1Jdr9ualNT85zBejA5gaNzWyhu_g&ci=145%2C153%2C850%2C1218&edge=0 p.&nbsp;578] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA579&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U2Rk6I2S3WZ-VvXhBVX3v3oCyx-pA&ci=30%2C177%2C820%2C1222&edge=0 p.&nbsp;579] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA580&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U1PmV9f9FK7qNm4lRHELMx1r21J0w&ci=160%2C155%2C820%2C1207&edge=0 p.&nbsp;580] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA581&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U2GZFEn330Ow6TUcwCANdbjK6R7Zw&ci=37%2C168%2C810%2C1212&edge=0 p.&nbsp;581] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pd3fAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA582&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U1b3Y5ZqALeLzM2O3ysYLq07Qh-pQ&ci=160%2C169%2C800%2C664&edge=0 p.&nbsp;582] at Google Books}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Assessors of Maat====\n{{Further|Assessors of Maat}}\nThe [[Assessors of Maat]] are the 42 deities listed in the ''Papyrus of Nebseni'',<ref name=\"Nebseni\">{{cite web|url=https://www.touregypt.net/bod123.htm|title=Papyrus of Nebseni|accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> to whom the deceased make the Negative Confession in the ''[[Papyrus of Ani]]''.<ref>Budge ''The Gods of the Egyptians'' Vol. 1 pp. 418\u201320</ref> They represent the 42 united [[Nome (Egypt)|nomes]] of Egypt, and are called \"the hidden Maati gods, who feed upon Maat during the years of their lives;\" i.e., they are the righteous minor deities who deserve offerings.<ref name=\"Ani\" /> As the deceased follows the set formula of Negative Confessions, he addresses each god directly and mentions the nome of which the god is a patron, in order to emphasize the unity of the nomes of Egypt.<ref name=\"Nebseni\" />\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"190\" heights=\"154\">\nFile:Offering maat.JPG|Statuette of a kneeling man, maybe a priest, offering a small Maat figure. Bronze with agemina. [[Third Intermediate Period]]/[[Late Period of ancient Egypt|Late Period]]\nFile:Deir el-Medina 2016-03-23j.jpg|Ancient artisans\u2019 village [[Deir el-Medina]] in [[Upper Egypt]]\nFile:Edfu22.JPG|[[Relief]] of Maat in east upstairs. [[Temple of Edfu]], Upper Egypt\nFile:Flickr - archer10 (Dennis) - Egypt-5A-044.jpg|Depiction of the Feast of the Beautiful Meeting, the second reunion between [[Horus]] and his wife [[Hathor]]. Temple of Edfu, Upper Egypt\nFile:RamessesIX-OstraconPresentingMaat MetropolitanMuseum.png|[[Ostracon]] depicting the pharaoh [[Ramesses IX]] presenting Maat\nFile:Temple of Deir el-Medina 13.JPG|Relief in the inner room of Hathor's temple in Deir el-Medina\nFile:Osiris E9418 mp3h8805.jpg|Maat represented with wings\n\nFile:\u0411\u0430\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0444 \u0441 \u0438\u0437\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u0435\u0433\u0438\u043f\u0442\u044f\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0441\u043e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0443\u044d\u0442\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u041c\u0430\u0430\u0442.jpg|[[Bas-relief]] depicting the Egyptian statuette of Maat. [[Old Kingdom]] \n</gallery>\n\n{{Portal|Traditional African religion}}\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Black, James Roger. ''[https://archive.is/20140430002426/https://www.shemtaia.com/diss.shtml The Instruction of Amenemope: A Critical Edition and Commentary&nbsp;\u2013 Prolegomenon and Prologue]'', Dissertation University of Wisconsin-Madison, 2002\n* [[E. A. Wallis Budge|Budge, E. A. Wallis]]. ''The Egyptian Book of the Dead: (The Papyrus of Ani) Egyptian Text Transliteration and Translation''. New York: Dover Publications, 1967. Originally published in 1895.\n* Budge, E. A. Wallis. ''The Gods of the Egyptians: Studies in Egyptian Mythology&nbsp;\u2013 Volume 1''. New York: Dover Publications, 1969. Originally published in 1904.\n* Collier, Mark and Manly, Bill. ''[[How to Read Egyptian Hieroglyphs]]: Revised Edition''. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1998.\n* Faulkner, Raymond. ''The Egyptian Book of the Dead''. San Francisco: Chronicle Books, 1994. {{ISBN|0-8118-6489-8}}\n* Mancini, Anna. ''Maat Revealed: Philosophy of Justice in Ancient Egypt''. New York: Buenos Books America, 2004.\n* Strudwick, Helen. (2006). ''The Encyclopedia of Ancient Egypt''. Singapore: De Agostini UK.\n* ''Journey through the afterlife, Ancient Egyptian Book of the Dead'' edited by John H. Taylor ([[the British Museum Press]] 2010. London {{ISBN|0-7141-1989-X}})\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Jan Assmann|Assmann, Jan]] (1990). ''Ma\u02bdat: Gerechtigkeit und Unsterblichkeit im Alten \u00c4gypten'' (in German). C.H. Beck Verlag. {{ISBN|3406346677}}.\n* Menu, Bernadette (2005). ''Ma\u00e2t: L'ordre juste du monde'' (in French). Editions Michalon. {{ISBN|2841862836}}.\n\n{{Ancient Egyptian religion footer|collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Egyptian goddesses]]\n[[Category:Justice goddesses]]\n[[Category:Ancient Near East law]]\n[[Category:Ancient Egyptian concepts]]\n[[Category:Book of the Dead]]\n", "name_user": "Uanfala", "label": "safe", "comment": "simpler template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maat"}
{"title_page": "Rufus (Kim Possible)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Rufus (''Kim Possible'')}} \n{{Infobox character\n| color              = \n| series             = [[Kim Possible]]\n| name               = Rufus\n| image              = [[File:Rufus_Kim_Possible.png|250px]]\n| caption            = \n| first              = \"Crush\" (2002)\n| last               = \"Graduation\" (2007)\n| creator            = [[Bob Schooley]]<br>[[Mark McCorkle]]\n| voice              = [[Nancy Cartwright]]\n| full_name          = \n| nickname           = \n| nationality        = \n| species            = [[Naked mole-rat]]\n| occupation         = \n| lbl22              = \n| data22             = \n| family             = \n| franchise          = [[Kim Possible]]\n| first_minor        =\n}}\n\n{{short description|Fictional character}}\n'''Rufus''' is a fictional character in the American animated television series ''[[Kim Possible]]'' (2002-2007) and its [[Kim Possible (2019 film)|2019 live-action film adaptation]]. Voiced by actress [[Nancy Cartwright]], Rufus is a pet [[naked mole-rat]] owned by Ron Stoppable, [[Kim Possible (character)|Kim Possible]]'s best friend and sidekick, and first appears in the show's [[Pilot Episode|pilot episode]] \"Crush\", which premiered on June 7, 2002. Residing and traveling in his owner's pocket, Rufus accompanies Kim and Ron on missions to protect the world from evildoers, at times proving beneficial to their success.\n\nSeries creators [[Bob Schooley]] and [[Mark McCorkle]] created Rufus at the behest of [[Disney Channel]] executives who insisted that the animated series required an animal sidekick, conceiving the character as a naked mole-rat to trick the network into saying the word \"naked\" whenever the character is mentioned. The writers took several [[Artistic License|creative liberties]] that differentiated Rufus from real naked mole-rats, such as a longer lifespan. The character is [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]], but apart from the occasional spoken word communicates using mostly squeaks and giggles, improvised by Cartwright. After considering having the character portrayed by either a live or puppeted mole rat in the live-action film, the filmmakers opted to make Rufus computer-animated instead, spending several months finalizing a design that was realistic yet appealing.\n\nThe character has been called a [[Breakout character|fan favorite]] and one of the series' most popular characters. Cartwright was nominated for a [[Daytime Emmy Award]] for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Performer in an Animated Program|Outstanding Performer in an Animated Program]] for her performance. Rufus has also been named the most famous naked mole-rat by various media and scientific publications, and is credited with introducing the species into mainstream popular culture.\n\n== Role ==\nRufus is the [[anthropomorphic]] pet naked mole-rat of Ron Stoppable,<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/will-rufus-be-in-the-new-kim-possible-movie-heres-what-the-naked-mole-rat-looks-like-15808346|title=Will Rufus Be In The New 'Kim Possible' Movie? Here's What The Naked Mole Rat Looks Like|last=Kickman|first=Dylan|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[Elite Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129065148/https://www.elitedaily.com/p/will-rufus-be-in-the-new-kim-possible-movie-heres-what-the-naked-mole-rat-looks-like-15808346|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> who is [[Kim Possible (character)|Kim Possible]]'s best friend and sidekick.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/patton-oswalt-sean-giambrone-todd-stashwick-and-taylor-ortega-form-a-c-136815|title=Patton Oswalt, Sean Giambrone, Todd Stashwick, and Taylor Ortega form a comedy dream team in Disney\u2019s \u2018Kim Possible\u2019|last=Cohen|first=Sari|date=February 14, 2019|website=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128213222/https://www.axs.com/patton-oswalt-sean-giambrone-todd-stashwick-and-taylor-ortega-form-a-c-136815|archive-date=January 28, 2020|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> Living and traveling in Ron's pants pocket,<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/streaming/2019/11/stream-kim-possible/|title=How to Stream \u2018Kim Possible\u2019: Your Ultimate Viewing Guide|last=|first=|date=2019|website=[[Heavy.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Rufus accompanies Kim and Ron on international missions as a member Team Possible,<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stemjobs.com/naked-mole-rats-and-cancer/|title=A Possible Superhero in the Fight Against Cancer|last=|first=|date=April 7, 2016|website=STEM Jobs|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410120053/https://www.stemjobs.com/naked-mole-rats-and-cancer/|archive-date=April 10, 2016|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> during which he sometimes jeopardizes their missions, which Kim ultimately resolves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/kim-possible-2496226299.html|title=Kim Possible|last=McLoone|first=Tracy|date=June 9, 2002|website=[[PopMatters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> However, Rufus has proven both intelligent and capable for a mole-rat, helping his teammates whenever possible and proving adept at overcoming electronic and mechanical obstacles,<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/752601/kim-possible-movie-rufus-naked-mole-rat/|title=Disney's 'Kim Possible' Movie: Get to Know Rufus, the Naked Mole Rat|last=Napoli|first=Jessica|date=February 14, 2019|website=[[TV Insider]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> typically emerging from Ron's pocket to either offer assistance or eat.<ref name=\":9\" /> Rufus also shares a strong affinity for nachos with Ron,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/heres-the-sitch-a-live-action-kim-possible-movie-is-coming-to-disney-channel|title=Here's the sitch: A live-action Kim Possible movie is coming to Disney Channel|last=Weiss|first=Josh|date=February 7, 2018|website=[[Syfy Wire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> and is considered to be his owner's best friend apart from Kim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/kim-possible|title=Kim Possible \u2013 Series Details & Credits|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Metacritic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Josh Weiss of [[SyFy Wire|Syfy Wire]] observed that the character \"is still capable of infectious energy and [[Nonverbal communication|non-verbal comedy]] all the same\", despite communicating mostly via squeaks and grunts.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/yes-rufus-will-be-in-the-live-action-kim-possible-movie-and-hell-be-voiced-by-bart-simpson|title=Yes, Rufus Will Be in the Live-action Kim Possible Movie and He'll Be Voiced by Bart Simpson|last=Weiss|first=Josh|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[Syfy Wire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128222620/https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/yes-rufus-will-be-in-the-live-action-kim-possible-movie-and-hell-be-voiced-by-bart-simpson|archive-date=January 28, 2020|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> \n\nRufus is one of the show's primary sources of [[comic relief]],<ref name=\":14\" /> alongside Ron.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/ae/tv/1440446|title=When Kim Possible battles evil, Romano speaks up|last=McDaniel|first=Mike|date=June 10, 2002|website=[[Houston Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020614055754/http://www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/ae/tv/1440446|archive-date=June 14, 2002|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> As revealed in the song \"The Naked Mole Rap\", a song written about Rufus,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/kim-possible-original-tv-soundtrack-mw0000599526|title=Original TV Soundtrack \u2013 Kim Possible [Original TV Soundtrack]|last=Phares|first=Heather|date=July 22, 2003|website=[[AllMusic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> Ron obtains Rufus because his father is [[Pet allergy|allergic to all animal furs]], forcing him to settle for a hairless pet.<ref name=\":6\" /> Ron discovers Rufus on the Internet.<ref name=\":6\" />\n== Development ==\n\n=== Creation and voice ===\n[[File:Nancy Cartwright 2012.jpg|thumb|268x268px|Actress [[Nancy Cartwright]] voices Rufus in both the television series and its live-action film adaption, using primarily a combination of improvised squeaks, gurgles and giggles.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":10\" />]]\nWriters [[Bob Schooley]] and [[Mark McCorkle]] conceived ''Kim Possible'' about a teenage girl who can seemingly do anything, and her best friend who struggles to do the same, after which Rufus was added once the show's \"basic foundation\" was written.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/2002/6/6/19659023/everything-is-kim-possible|title=Everything is 'Kim Possible'|last=Pierce|first=Scott D.|date=June 6, 2002|website=[[Deseret News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129200031/https://www.deseret.com/2002/6/6/19659023/everything-is-kim-possible|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Rufus was conceived at the behest of [[Disney Channel]] executives,<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/kim-possible-cartoon-makes-no-sense/|title=25 Things That Make No Sense About Kim Possible|last=Pirone|first=Kristy|date=April 16, 2019|website=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423105939/https://screenrant.com/kim-possible-cartoon-makes-no-sense/|archive-date=April 23, 2019|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> who insisted that [[Children's television series|children's animated series]] require at least one animal sidekick.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/kim-possible-dark-hidden-secrets-behind-making/|title=15 Secrets You Never Knew Behind The Making Of Kim Possible|last=Pereira|first=Sergio|date=December 4, 2017|website=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128204252/https://screenrant.com/kim-possible-dark-hidden-secrets-behind-making/|archive-date=January 28, 2020|access-date=January 28, 2020|quote=Ultimately, Rufus proved to be a popular character}}</ref> Already weary of constant network edits and suggestions,<ref name=\":12\" /> the creators tricked the executives by conceiving Rufus as a naked mole-rat, which in turn forces everyone to say the word \"naked\" whenever the character's species is mentioned throughout the children's program.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Despite the character's eventual popularity, the writers maintained using him sparingly throughout the series,<ref name=\":5\" /> in which he is \"only peppered in there occasionally\" apart from occasional brief episodes focusing on the character that are more gag-oriented.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://animesuperhero.com/toon-zone-interviews-bob-schooley-amp-mark-mccorkle-on-kim-possible-season-4/|title=Toon Zone Interviews Bob Schooley & Mark McCorkle on Kim Possible Season 4|last=Liu|first=Ed|date=February 9, 2007|website=Anime Superhero News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514094532/https://animesuperhero.com/toon-zone-interviews-bob-schooley-amp-mark-mccorkle-on-kim-possible-season-4/|archive-date=May 14, 2019|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRufus is voiced by American actress [[Nancy Cartwright]],<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/news/kim-possible-premieres|title=Kim Possible Premieres|last=Godfrey|first=Leigh|date=June 5, 2002|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> following a common trend in which animated male characters are voiced by women.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/kim-possible-trivia-facts-ron-stoppable/|title=15 Things You Didn't Know About Kim Possible|last=Ortiz|first=Danielle|date=June 13, 2017|website=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> Cartwright's dialogue for Rufus consists of almost entirely squeaks, gurgles and giggles, believing that the character offers comedy and \"a little levity to the show.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> However, the character occasionally utters words and phrases considered to be ''Kim Possible'' [[hallmark]]s, such as \"boo-yah\".<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://d23.com/kim-possible-rufus-is-back/|title=A Fan Fave Returns to the Screen in the Live-Action Kim Possible|last=Deitchman|first=Beth|date=February 14, 2019|website=[[D23 (Disney)|D23]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129065146/https://d23.com/kim-possible-rufus-is-back/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Cartwright researched naked mole-rats in preparation for the role, discovering that they \"are tunnel dwellers and social animals who live in large communities\" who also \"don\u2019t do well out in the sunlight\".<ref name=\":10\" /> Cartwright also found them to be \u201ckind of disgusting looking\", likening them to \"overcooked hot dogs.\u201d<ref name=\":10\" /> The actress typically improvised and performed the role without a written script, borrowing direction from the character's emotions during particular scenes that vary from excited to sad.<ref name=\":10\" /> Cartwright voiced Rufus while voicing [[Chuckie Finster]] from ''[[Rugrats]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/gallery/kim-possible-voices/?slide=271233#271233|title=Kim Possible Voices: See the Stars Behind Your Favorite Characters|last=Boardman|first=Madeline|date=August 26, 2016|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/nancy-cartwright-p11042|title=Nancy Cartwright|last=LeVasseur|first=Andrea|date=|website=[[AllMovie]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCartwright reprised her voice role in the show's [[Kim Possible (2019 film)|2019 live-action film adaptation]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/nancy-cartwright-kim-possible-rufus-disney-channel-movie-1202534836/|title=Nancy Cartwright Reprises \u2018Kim Possible\u2019 Rufus Role For Disney Channel Movie|last=Evans|first=Greg|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128205524/https://deadline.com/2019/01/nancy-cartwright-kim-possible-rufus-disney-channel-movie-1202534836/|archive-date=January 28, 2020|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Nancy-Cartwright-to-Reprise-Role-of-Rufus-in-Live-Action-KIM-POSSIBLE-20190114|title=Nancy Cartwright to Reprise Role of Rufus in Live-Action Kim Possible|last=|first=|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[BroadwayWorld]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128213221/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Nancy-Cartwright-to-Reprise-Role-of-Rufus-in-Live-Action-KIM-POSSIBLE-20190114|archive-date=January 28, 2020|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> having hoped Disney would invite her back once the project was announced.<ref name=\":10\" /> Cartwright considers Rufus the film's only truly animated aspect,<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=it&u=https://www.universalmovies.it/kim-possible-ecco-come-sara-la-talpa-rufus-nel-live-action/&prev=search|title=Kim Possible - This is what the mole Rufus will look like in live action|last=Febe|first=Massimino de|date=January 20, 2019|website=Universal Movies|language=Italian|via=[[Google Translate]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211163312/https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=it&u=https://www.universalmovies.it/kim-possible-ecco-come-sara-la-talpa-rufus-nel-live-action/&prev=search|archive-date=February 11, 2020|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref> hoping that the character's inclusion \"adds this little extra thing that inspires kids.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> Cartwright shared behind the scenes footage of herself voicing the character on her [[social media]] accounts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2019/01/19/Nancy-Cartwright-to-reprise-Rufus-voice-in-live-action-Kim-Possible/8541547921347/|title=Nancy Cartwright to reprise Rufus voice in live-action 'Kim Possible'|last=Butler|first=Karen|date=January 19, 2019|website=[[United Press International]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129075728/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2019/01/19/Nancy-Cartwright-to-reprise-Rufus-voice-in-live-action-Kim-Possible/8541547921347/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Actor [[Sean Giambrone]], who plays Ron in the film, expressed admiration for Cartwright's \"ability to bring Rufus to life with her voice\", feeling that he bonded with the character despite being unable to see or interact with him while filming.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2019/02/15/kim-possible-movie-live-action-disney-channel-reboot-cast-interview/|title=Kim Possible Stars Preview Live-Action Disney Channel Movie, Including the Original Kim's 'Perfect' Cameo|last=Swift|first=Andy|date=February 15, 2019|website=[[TVLine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129052756/https://tvline.com/2019/02/15/kim-possible-movie-live-action-disney-channel-reboot-cast-interview/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Despite being best known for voicing [[Bart Simpson]] in ''[[The Simpsons]]'',<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2019/02/14/disneys-live-action-kim-possible-brings-tech-savvy-heroine-new-generation-patton-oswalt-cameo/2865812002/|title=Disney's live-action 'Kim Possible' introduces new generation to high-tech heroine, airs Feb. 15|last=Haller|first=Sonja|date=February 14, 2019|website=[[USA Today]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129150134/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2019/02/14/disneys-live-action-kim-possible-brings-tech-savvy-heroine-new-generation-patton-oswalt-cameo/2865812002/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://movieweb.com/kim-possible-movie-cast-rufus-nancy-cartwright/|title=Kim Possible Movie Brings Back Nancy Cartwright as Rufus|last=Dick|first=Jeremy|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[MovieWeb]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129173314/https://movieweb.com/kim-possible-movie-cast-rufus-nancy-cartwright/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Cartwright considers voicing Rufus a highlight of her career, enjoying fans' surprised reactions when she demonstrates her Rufus impression for them: \"it\u2019s kind of surprising that I\u2019m like five feet tall, I\u2019ve got children of my own, I\u2019m a grandma, and these sounds come out of this little package here. I think it\u2019s fun for everyone\u201d.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n=== Design and characterization ===\nRufus differs significantly from real naked mole-rats found in nature. Unlike the character, naked mole-rats are unlikely to survive if [[Domestication|kept as pets]] and prone to die in captivity.<ref name=\":12\" /> Rufus' lifespan is also uncharacteristically long for a naked mole-rat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/three-grow|title=Three to Grow On|last=Goodman|first=Martin|date=May 14, 2004|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514100037/https://www.awn.com/animationworld/three-grow|archive-date=May 14, 2019|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> When the live-action adaptation of ''Kim Possible'' was first [[Green-light|green-lit]], the directors had considered having a live mole-rat portray Rufus, but Schooley and McCorkle determined that this would not benefit the creature itself or viewers, opting for the character to be [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] instead.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/reeling-in-the-new-live-action-kim-possible-movie/|title=Reeling in the New Live-Action \u2018Kim Possible\u2019 Movie|last=Zahed|first=Ramin|date=February 13, 2019|website=[[Animation Magazine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219032612/https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/reeling-in-the-new-live-action-kim-possible-movie/|archive-date=February 19, 2019|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> 15 years prior, the original series had aired an episode jokingly entitled \"And the Mole Rat Will Be CGI\" revolving around Hollywood filmmakers and actors producing a film based on Kim's life.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/kcbw/kim-possible--s3-e12-kim-possible-special-and-the-mole-rat-will-be-cgi/|title=Kim Possible Special: And the Mole Rat Will Be CGI|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Radio Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130170648/https://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/kcbw/kim-possible--s3-e12-kim-possible-special-and-the-mole-rat-will-be-cgi/|archive-date=January 30, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBefore deciding on CGI, the filmmakers had also considered depicting Rufus using puppets before ultimately determining that computer animation was \"the only way to capture his expressiveness ... We really worked hard with the animators to make him feel real, because we didn\u2019t want a [[Who Framed Roger Rabbit|''Roger Rabbit'']] situation going on where the world is live-action and then you have this cartoon character. We wanted Rufus to be part of their world and grounded, even though he is expressive, cute and fun.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> The visual effects studio [[Pixomondo]] was responsible for animating Rufus, a task they found challenging because, according to director [[Zach Lipovsky]], the animals \"are pretty disgusting creatures\", finding it \"hilarious to have one of the grossest animals be the [show and film's] comedic relief.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Because the computer-animated character needed to be more realistic than his cuter, stylized [[Traditional animation|traditionally animated]] counterpart, the Pixomondo artists worked for several months to determine a suitable \"balance between cute and real\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe character's origins and his relationship with Ron are altered for the film, in which Ron discovers Rufus in a science lab.<ref name=\":6\" /> Giambrone explained, \"Ron knew that that [Rufus] was like a missing part of him ... Then we get to see how they help each other out for the rest of the movie\".<ref name=\":6\" /> The actors did not see Rufus's final design until the character's visual effects were completely rendered, instead looking at either Giambrone's shoulder or a figurine that they found hardly resembled Rufus while filming.<ref name=\":10\" /> Giambrone was pleased with the character's design upon seeing it for the first time, expounding, \"I knew that was exactly what he should look like and it just felt like I was reunited with a buddy, seeing the movie with Rufus in it.\u201d<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n== Reception and impact ==\n''[[The New York Times]]'' television critic [[Julie Salamon]] wrote that \"the cheerful presence of Rufus ... signals that the show's executive producer and director, [[Chris Bailey (animator)|Chris Bailey]], doesn't mind getting cute in obvious ways.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/07/movies/tv-weekend-a-superhero-as-retro-as-she-s-cool.html|title=TV Weekend; A Superhero As Retro As She's Cool|last=Salamon|first=Julie|authorlink=Julie Salamon|date=June 7, 2002|website=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131173456/https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/07/movies/tv-weekend-a-superhero-as-retro-as-she-s-cool.html|archive-date=January 31, 2020|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]''<nowiki/>'s Alex Kane cited Rufus among the show's \"charming cast\" of memorable characters,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/reviewedcom/2019/11/12/how-to-watch-kim-possible-disney-plus/2564136001/|title=How to watch Kim Possible|last=Kane|first=Alex|date=November 12, 2019|website=[[USA Today]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131173457/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/reviewedcom/2019/11/12/how-to-watch-kim-possible-disney-plus/2564136001/|archive-date=January 31, 2020|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> while the ''[[Post-Gazette|Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]''<nowiki/>'s [[Rob Owen (journalist)|Rob Owen]] identified Rufus as the show's [[breakout character]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/tv/20020607owen0607fnp3.asp|title=On the Tube: Animated 'Kim Possible' new brand of action hero|last=Owen|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Owen (journalist)|date=June 7, 2002|website=[[Post-Gazette]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513193625/http://old.post-gazette.com/tv/20020607owen0607fnp3.asp|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> Rufus is considered one of the show's most popular characters and components,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> establishing himself as a fan favorite.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/nancy-cartwright-returns-as-rufus-in-kim-possible/|title=Nancy Cartwright Returns as Rufus in \u2018Kim Possible\u2019|last=Milligan|first=Mercedes|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[Animation Magazine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129074217/https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/nancy-cartwright-returns-as-rufus-in-kim-possible/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://d23.com/kim-possibles-fan-fave-rufus-captain-marvel-posters-plus-news-briefs/|title=Rufus the Naked Mole-Rat is Back in Live-Action Kim Possible|last=Potter|first=Courtney|date=January 17, 2019|website=[[D23 (Disney)|D23]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129172808/https://d23.com/kim-possibles-fan-fave-rufus-captain-marvel-posters-plus-news-briefs/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> McCorkle believes Rufus is the series' most popular character among younger viewers,<ref name=\":0\" /> an observation with which Judith S. Gillies of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' agreed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/tv/2002/06/16/kim-possible-leads-summers-fresh-fare/37a0ad3f-9eb7-4632-8565-8e952e7ef2e4/|title='Kim Possible' Leads Summer's Fresh Fare|last=Gillies|first=Judith S.|date=June 16, 2002|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref> Dylan Kickham of ''[[Elite Daily]]'' named Rufus both \"iconic\" and \"Everyone's favorite naked mole-rat\".<ref name=\":9\" /> Similarly, the ''[[Rockford Register Star]]'' called Rufus \"our favorite naked mole-rat\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rrstar.com/entertainment/20180811/holy-naked-mole-rat-kim-possible-live-action-movie-is-going-meta|title=Holy Naked Mole Rat! The Kim Possible Live-Action Movie Is Going Meta|last=|first=|date=August 11, 2018|website=[[Rockford Register Star]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Andy Swift of ''[[TVLine]]'' deemed Rufus an \"iconic\" character.<ref name=\":8\" /> Furthermore, Kickham believes Rufus' role in the series is \"the reason why so many young adults have actually heard of naked mole-rats.\"<ref name=\":9\" /> Cartwright's performance earned her a [[Daytime Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Performer in an Animated Program|Outstanding Performer in an Animated Program]] at the [[31st Daytime Emmy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/daytime-emmy-noms-unveiled/|title=Daytime Emmy Noms Unveiled|last=Ball|first=Ryan|date=March 4, 2004|website=[[Animation Magazine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130160935/https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/daytime-emmy-noms-unveiled/|archive-date=January 30, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/news/duck-dodgers-leads-daytime-emmy-nominations|title=Duck Dodgers Leads Daytime Emmy Nominations|last=Baisley|first=Sarah|date=March 4, 2004|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130161207/https://www.awn.com/news/duck-dodgers-leads-daytime-emmy-nominations|archive-date=January 30, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> [[MovieWeb]]'s Jeremy Dick hailed Rufus as \"one of Cartwright's best roles\".<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nFans of the series were initially outraged when the film adaptation's first trailer did not feature Rufus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/movies/2018/12/07/kim-possible-live-action-movie-trailer-rufus-naked-mole-rat/#1|title='Kim Possible' Fans in Uproar Over No Naked Mole Rat in Live-Action Trailer|last=Outlaw|first=Kofi|date=December 7, 2018|website=Comic Book|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129074254/https://comicbook.com/movies/2018/12/07/kim-possible-live-action-movie-trailer-rufus-naked-mole-rat/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Fans were eventually delighted to learn that Cartwright would be reprising her role in the film.<ref name=\":11\" /> While Blair Marnell of [[Nerdist News|Nerdist]] opined that producers should be open to recasting the film's main characters in favor of more diverse actors, she insisted that \"As long as Nancy Cartwright wants to reprise her role as the voice of Rufus, she should be able to do that for life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.nerdist.com/kim-possible-live-action-tv-movie-disney/|title=Kim Possible's Coming Back As a Live-action TV Movie|last=Marnelll|first=Blair|date=February 7, 2018|website=[[Nerdist News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref> Reviewing the film, [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'s Petrana Radulovic described Rufus as \"just silly enough as to not be jarring.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/tv/2019/2/15/18226603/kim-possible-live-action-movie-review|title=Kim Possible deserves a place among DCOM classics|last=Radulovic|first=Petrana|date=February 15, 2019|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Despite being disappointed with the overall film and Rufus' comparative lack of screentime, Aydan Rossovich of ''The Bear River Current'' felt he was \"The only acceptable character ... while it\u2019s disappointing that he was barely in it, if he had been in the movie more than he was, it would have just made it even more annoying.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brcurrent.com/index.php/2019/03/13/review-disneys-kim-possible-movie-disappoints-childhood-fans/|title=Review: Disney\u2019s \"Kim Possible\" movie disappoints childhood fans|last=Rossovich|first=Aydan|date=March 13, 2019|website=The Bear River Current|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] Jobs crowned Rufus \"one of the most faithful, yet smallest sidekicks of all time.\"<ref name=\":14\" /> Rufus has been called the most famous naked mole-rat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tulsazoo.org/naked-mole-rat-pups-born-at-the-tulsa-zoo/|title=Naked Mole Rat Pups Born at the Tulsa Zoo|last=|first=|date=|website=The Tulsa Zoo|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129161909/https://tulsazoo.org/naked-mole-rat-pups-born-at-the-tulsa-zoo/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020|quote=The most famous naked mole rat is the fictional Rufus character from Kim Possible.}}</ref> Kristy Pirone of ''[[Screen Rant]]'' believes Rufus \"will live in perpetuity as the most famous naked mole-rat of all time.\"<ref name=\":12\" /> Massive Science credits Rufus and ''Kim Possible'' with introducing naked mole-rats into mainstream popular culture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://massivesci.com/articles/naked-mole-rats-aging-cancer/|title=Do naked mole rats hold the answers to cancer prevention and aging?|last=Shepard|first=Alyssa|date=June 28, 2018|website=Massive Science|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129174520/https://massivesci.com/articles/naked-mole-rats-aging-cancer/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> The [[Liberty Science Center]] observed that most people may \"only know about naked mole rats via cartoon characters\", such as Rufus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lsc.org/news-and-social/news/naked-mole-rats-have-arrived-at-liberty-science-center|title=Naked mole rats have arrived at Liberty Science Center|last=|first=|date=January 11, 2017|website=[[Liberty Science Center]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204171700/https://lsc.org/news-and-social/news/naked-mole-rats-have-arrived-at-liberty-science-center|archive-date=February 4, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> The [[Field Museum of Natural History]] wrote that \"Rufus stole the hearts of all who watched him save the day. In many episodes, Rufus is the hero, and like Kim and Ron, scientists agree that naked mole-rats are pretty cool.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fieldmuseum.org/blog/naked-mole-rats-not-mole-not-rat-and-not-african-mole-rat|title=Naked mole-rats: Not a mole, not a rat, and not an African mole-rat|last=Gaare|first=Megan|date=December 1, 2014|website=[[Field Museum of Natural History]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195036/https://www.fieldmuseum.org/blog/naked-mole-rats-not-mole-not-rat-and-not-african-mole-rat|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{KimPossible|state=expanded}}\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2002]]\n[[Category:Fictional rodents]]\n[[Category:Television sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Anthropomorphic animal characters]]\n[[Category:Anthropomorphic rodents]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Rufus (''Kim Possible'')}} \n{{Infobox character\n| color              = \n| series             = [[Kim Possible]]\n| name               = Rufus\n| image              = [[File:Rufus_Kim_Possible.png|250px]]\n| caption            = \n| first              = \"Crush\" (2002)\n| creator            = [[Bob Schooley]]<br>[[Mark McCorkle]]\n| voice              = [[Nancy Cartwright]]\n| full_name          = \n| nickname           = \n| nationality        = \n| species            = [[Naked mole-rat]]\n| occupation         = \n| lbl22              = \n| data22             = \n| family             = \n| franchise          = [[Kim Possible]]\n| first_minor        =\n}}\n\n{{short description|Fictional character}}\n'''Rufus''' is a fictional character in the American animated television series ''[[Kim Possible]]'' (2002-2007) and its [[Kim Possible (2019 film)|2019 live-action film adaptation]]. Voiced by actress [[Nancy Cartwright]], Rufus is a pet [[naked mole-rat]] owned by Ron Stoppable, [[Kim Possible (character)|Kim Possible]]'s best friend and sidekick, and first appears in the show's [[Pilot Episode|pilot episode]] \"Crush\", which premiered on June 7, 2002. Residing and traveling in his owner's pocket, Rufus accompanies Kim and Ron on missions to protect the world from evildoers, at times proving beneficial to their success.\n\nSeries creators [[Bob Schooley]] and [[Mark McCorkle]] created Rufus at the behest of [[Disney Channel]] executives who insisted that the animated series required an animal sidekick, conceiving the character as a naked mole-rat to trick the network into saying the word \"naked\" whenever the character is mentioned. The writers took several [[Artistic License|creative liberties]] that differentiated Rufus from real naked mole-rats, such as a longer lifespan. The character is [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]], but apart from the occasional spoken word communicates using mostly squeaks and giggles, improvised by Cartwright. After considering having the character portrayed by either a live or puppeted mole rat in the live-action film, the filmmakers opted to make Rufus computer-animated instead, spending several months finalizing a design that was realistic yet appealing.\n\nThe character has been called a [[Breakout character|fan favorite]] and one of the series' most popular characters. Cartwright was nominated for a [[Daytime Emmy Award]] for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Performer in an Animated Program|Outstanding Performer in an Animated Program]] for her performance. Rufus has also been named the most famous naked mole-rat by various media and scientific publications, and is credited with introducing the species into mainstream popular culture.\n\n== Role ==\nRufus is the [[anthropomorphic]] pet naked mole-rat of Ron Stoppable,<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/will-rufus-be-in-the-new-kim-possible-movie-heres-what-the-naked-mole-rat-looks-like-15808346|title=Will Rufus Be In The New 'Kim Possible' Movie? Here's What The Naked Mole Rat Looks Like|last=Kickman|first=Dylan|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[Elite Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129065148/https://www.elitedaily.com/p/will-rufus-be-in-the-new-kim-possible-movie-heres-what-the-naked-mole-rat-looks-like-15808346|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> who is [[Kim Possible (character)|Kim Possible]]'s best friend and sidekick.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/patton-oswalt-sean-giambrone-todd-stashwick-and-taylor-ortega-form-a-c-136815|title=Patton Oswalt, Sean Giambrone, Todd Stashwick, and Taylor Ortega form a comedy dream team in Disney\u2019s \u2018Kim Possible\u2019|last=Cohen|first=Sari|date=February 14, 2019|website=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128213222/https://www.axs.com/patton-oswalt-sean-giambrone-todd-stashwick-and-taylor-ortega-form-a-c-136815|archive-date=January 28, 2020|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> Living and traveling in Ron's pants pocket,<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/streaming/2019/11/stream-kim-possible/|title=How to Stream \u2018Kim Possible\u2019: Your Ultimate Viewing Guide|last=|first=|date=2019|website=[[Heavy.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Rufus accompanies Kim and Ron on international missions as a member Team Possible,<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stemjobs.com/naked-mole-rats-and-cancer/|title=A Possible Superhero in the Fight Against Cancer|last=|first=|date=April 7, 2016|website=STEM Jobs|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410120053/https://www.stemjobs.com/naked-mole-rats-and-cancer/|archive-date=April 10, 2016|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> during which he sometimes jeopardizes their missions, which Kim ultimately resolves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/kim-possible-2496226299.html|title=Kim Possible|last=McLoone|first=Tracy|date=June 9, 2002|website=[[PopMatters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> However, Rufus has proven both intelligent and capable for a mole-rat, helping his teammates whenever possible and proving adept at overcoming electronic and mechanical obstacles,<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/752601/kim-possible-movie-rufus-naked-mole-rat/|title=Disney's 'Kim Possible' Movie: Get to Know Rufus, the Naked Mole Rat|last=Napoli|first=Jessica|date=February 14, 2019|website=[[TV Insider]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> typically emerging from Ron's pocket to either offer assistance or eat.<ref name=\":9\" /> Rufus also shares a strong affinity for nachos with Ron,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/heres-the-sitch-a-live-action-kim-possible-movie-is-coming-to-disney-channel|title=Here's the sitch: A live-action Kim Possible movie is coming to Disney Channel|last=Weiss|first=Josh|date=February 7, 2018|website=[[Syfy Wire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> and is considered to be his owner's best friend apart from Kim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/kim-possible|title=Kim Possible \u2013 Series Details & Credits|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Metacritic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Josh Weiss of [[SyFy Wire|Syfy Wire]] observed that the character \"is still capable of infectious energy and [[Nonverbal communication|non-verbal comedy]] all the same\", despite communicating mostly via squeaks and grunts.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/yes-rufus-will-be-in-the-live-action-kim-possible-movie-and-hell-be-voiced-by-bart-simpson|title=Yes, Rufus Will Be in the Live-action Kim Possible Movie and He'll Be Voiced by Bart Simpson|last=Weiss|first=Josh|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[Syfy Wire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128222620/https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/yes-rufus-will-be-in-the-live-action-kim-possible-movie-and-hell-be-voiced-by-bart-simpson|archive-date=January 28, 2020|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> \n\nRufus is one of the show's primary sources of [[comic relief]],<ref name=\":14\" /> alongside Ron.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/ae/tv/1440446|title=When Kim Possible battles evil, Romano speaks up|last=McDaniel|first=Mike|date=June 10, 2002|website=[[Houston Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020614055754/http://www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/ae/tv/1440446|archive-date=June 14, 2002|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> As revealed in the song \"The Naked Mole Rap\", a song written about Rufus,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/kim-possible-original-tv-soundtrack-mw0000599526|title=Original TV Soundtrack \u2013 Kim Possible [Original TV Soundtrack]|last=Phares|first=Heather|date=July 22, 2003|website=[[AllMusic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> Ron obtains Rufus because his father is [[Pet allergy|allergic to all animal furs]], forcing him to settle for a hairless pet.<ref name=\":6\" /> Ron discovers Rufus on the Internet.<ref name=\":6\" />\n== Development ==\n\n=== Creation and voice ===\n[[File:Nancy Cartwright 2012.jpg|thumb|268x268px|Actress [[Nancy Cartwright]] voices Rufus in both the television series and its live-action film adaption, using primarily a combination of improvised squeaks, gurgles and giggles.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":10\" />]]\nWriters [[Bob Schooley]] and [[Mark McCorkle]] conceived ''Kim Possible'' about a teenage girl who can seemingly do anything, and her best friend who struggles to do the same, after which Rufus was added once the show's \"basic foundation\" was written.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/2002/6/6/19659023/everything-is-kim-possible|title=Everything is 'Kim Possible'|last=Pierce|first=Scott D.|date=June 6, 2002|website=[[Deseret News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129200031/https://www.deseret.com/2002/6/6/19659023/everything-is-kim-possible|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Rufus was conceived at the behest of [[Disney Channel]] executives,<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/kim-possible-cartoon-makes-no-sense/|title=25 Things That Make No Sense About Kim Possible|last=Pirone|first=Kristy|date=April 16, 2019|website=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423105939/https://screenrant.com/kim-possible-cartoon-makes-no-sense/|archive-date=April 23, 2019|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> who insisted that [[Children's television series|children's animated series]] require at least one animal sidekick.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/kim-possible-dark-hidden-secrets-behind-making/|title=15 Secrets You Never Knew Behind The Making Of Kim Possible|last=Pereira|first=Sergio|date=December 4, 2017|website=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128204252/https://screenrant.com/kim-possible-dark-hidden-secrets-behind-making/|archive-date=January 28, 2020|access-date=January 28, 2020|quote=Ultimately, Rufus proved to be a popular character}}</ref> Already weary of constant network edits and suggestions,<ref name=\":12\" /> the creators tricked the executives by conceiving Rufus as a naked mole-rat, which in turn forces everyone to say the word \"naked\" whenever the character's species is mentioned throughout the children's program.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Despite the character's eventual popularity, the writers maintained using him sparingly throughout the series,<ref name=\":5\" /> in which he is \"only peppered in there occasionally\" apart from occasional brief episodes focusing on the character that are more gag-oriented.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://animesuperhero.com/toon-zone-interviews-bob-schooley-amp-mark-mccorkle-on-kim-possible-season-4/|title=Toon Zone Interviews Bob Schooley & Mark McCorkle on Kim Possible Season 4|last=Liu|first=Ed|date=February 9, 2007|website=Anime Superhero News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514094532/https://animesuperhero.com/toon-zone-interviews-bob-schooley-amp-mark-mccorkle-on-kim-possible-season-4/|archive-date=May 14, 2019|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRufus is voiced by American actress [[Nancy Cartwright]],<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/news/kim-possible-premieres|title=Kim Possible Premieres|last=Godfrey|first=Leigh|date=June 5, 2002|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> following a common trend in which animated male characters are voiced by women.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/kim-possible-trivia-facts-ron-stoppable/|title=15 Things You Didn't Know About Kim Possible|last=Ortiz|first=Danielle|date=June 13, 2017|website=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> Cartwright's dialogue for Rufus consists of almost entirely squeaks, gurgles and giggles, believing that the character offers comedy and \"a little levity to the show.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> However, the character occasionally utters words and phrases considered to be ''Kim Possible'' [[hallmark]]s, such as \"boo-yah\".<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://d23.com/kim-possible-rufus-is-back/|title=A Fan Fave Returns to the Screen in the Live-Action Kim Possible|last=Deitchman|first=Beth|date=February 14, 2019|website=[[D23 (Disney)|D23]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129065146/https://d23.com/kim-possible-rufus-is-back/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Cartwright researched naked mole-rats in preparation for the role, discovering that they \"are tunnel dwellers and social animals who live in large communities\" who also \"don\u2019t do well out in the sunlight\".<ref name=\":10\" /> Cartwright also found them to be \u201ckind of disgusting looking\", likening them to \"overcooked hot dogs.\u201d<ref name=\":10\" /> The actress typically improvised and performed the role without a written script, borrowing direction from the character's emotions during particular scenes that vary from excited to sad.<ref name=\":10\" /> Cartwright voiced Rufus while voicing [[Chuckie Finster]] from ''[[Rugrats]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/gallery/kim-possible-voices/?slide=271233#271233|title=Kim Possible Voices: See the Stars Behind Your Favorite Characters|last=Boardman|first=Madeline|date=August 26, 2016|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/nancy-cartwright-p11042|title=Nancy Cartwright|last=LeVasseur|first=Andrea|date=|website=[[AllMovie]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCartwright reprised her voice role in the show's [[Kim Possible (2019 film)|2019 live-action film adaptation]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/nancy-cartwright-kim-possible-rufus-disney-channel-movie-1202534836/|title=Nancy Cartwright Reprises \u2018Kim Possible\u2019 Rufus Role For Disney Channel Movie|last=Evans|first=Greg|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128205524/https://deadline.com/2019/01/nancy-cartwright-kim-possible-rufus-disney-channel-movie-1202534836/|archive-date=January 28, 2020|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Nancy-Cartwright-to-Reprise-Role-of-Rufus-in-Live-Action-KIM-POSSIBLE-20190114|title=Nancy Cartwright to Reprise Role of Rufus in Live-Action Kim Possible|last=|first=|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[BroadwayWorld]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128213221/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Nancy-Cartwright-to-Reprise-Role-of-Rufus-in-Live-Action-KIM-POSSIBLE-20190114|archive-date=January 28, 2020|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> having hoped Disney would invite her back once the project was announced.<ref name=\":10\" /> Cartwright considers Rufus the film's only truly animated aspect,<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=it&u=https://www.universalmovies.it/kim-possible-ecco-come-sara-la-talpa-rufus-nel-live-action/&prev=search|title=Kim Possible - This is what the mole Rufus will look like in live action|last=Febe|first=Massimino de|date=January 20, 2019|website=Universal Movies|language=Italian|via=[[Google Translate]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211163312/https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=it&u=https://www.universalmovies.it/kim-possible-ecco-come-sara-la-talpa-rufus-nel-live-action/&prev=search|archive-date=February 11, 2020|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref> hoping that the character's inclusion \"adds this little extra thing that inspires kids.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> Cartwright shared behind the scenes footage of herself voicing the character on her [[social media]] accounts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2019/01/19/Nancy-Cartwright-to-reprise-Rufus-voice-in-live-action-Kim-Possible/8541547921347/|title=Nancy Cartwright to reprise Rufus voice in live-action 'Kim Possible'|last=Butler|first=Karen|date=January 19, 2019|website=[[United Press International]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129075728/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2019/01/19/Nancy-Cartwright-to-reprise-Rufus-voice-in-live-action-Kim-Possible/8541547921347/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Actor [[Sean Giambrone]], who plays Ron in the film, expressed admiration for Cartwright's \"ability to bring Rufus to life with her voice\", feeling that he bonded with the character despite being unable to see or interact with him while filming.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2019/02/15/kim-possible-movie-live-action-disney-channel-reboot-cast-interview/|title=Kim Possible Stars Preview Live-Action Disney Channel Movie, Including the Original Kim's 'Perfect' Cameo|last=Swift|first=Andy|date=February 15, 2019|website=[[TVLine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129052756/https://tvline.com/2019/02/15/kim-possible-movie-live-action-disney-channel-reboot-cast-interview/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Despite being best known for voicing [[Bart Simpson]] in ''[[The Simpsons]]'',<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2019/02/14/disneys-live-action-kim-possible-brings-tech-savvy-heroine-new-generation-patton-oswalt-cameo/2865812002/|title=Disney's live-action 'Kim Possible' introduces new generation to high-tech heroine, airs Feb. 15|last=Haller|first=Sonja|date=February 14, 2019|website=[[USA Today]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129150134/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2019/02/14/disneys-live-action-kim-possible-brings-tech-savvy-heroine-new-generation-patton-oswalt-cameo/2865812002/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://movieweb.com/kim-possible-movie-cast-rufus-nancy-cartwright/|title=Kim Possible Movie Brings Back Nancy Cartwright as Rufus|last=Dick|first=Jeremy|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[MovieWeb]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129173314/https://movieweb.com/kim-possible-movie-cast-rufus-nancy-cartwright/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Cartwright considers voicing Rufus a highlight of her career, enjoying fans' surprised reactions when she demonstrates her Rufus impression for them: \"it\u2019s kind of surprising that I\u2019m like five feet tall, I\u2019ve got children of my own, I\u2019m a grandma, and these sounds come out of this little package here. I think it\u2019s fun for everyone\u201d.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n=== Design and characterization ===\nRufus differs significantly from real naked mole-rats found in nature. Unlike the character, naked mole-rats are unlikely to survive if [[Domestication|kept as pets]] and prone to die in captivity.<ref name=\":12\" /> Rufus' lifespan is also uncharacteristically long for a naked mole-rat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/three-grow|title=Three to Grow On|last=Goodman|first=Martin|date=May 14, 2004|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514100037/https://www.awn.com/animationworld/three-grow|archive-date=May 14, 2019|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> When the live-action adaptation of ''Kim Possible'' was first [[Green-light|green-lit]], the directors had considered having a live mole-rat portray Rufus, but Schooley and McCorkle determined that this would not benefit the creature itself or viewers, opting for the character to be [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] instead.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/reeling-in-the-new-live-action-kim-possible-movie/|title=Reeling in the New Live-Action \u2018Kim Possible\u2019 Movie|last=Zahed|first=Ramin|date=February 13, 2019|website=[[Animation Magazine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219032612/https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/reeling-in-the-new-live-action-kim-possible-movie/|archive-date=February 19, 2019|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> 15 years prior, the original series had aired an episode jokingly entitled \"And the Mole Rat Will Be CGI\" revolving around Hollywood filmmakers and actors producing a film based on Kim's life.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/kcbw/kim-possible--s3-e12-kim-possible-special-and-the-mole-rat-will-be-cgi/|title=Kim Possible Special: And the Mole Rat Will Be CGI|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Radio Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130170648/https://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/kcbw/kim-possible--s3-e12-kim-possible-special-and-the-mole-rat-will-be-cgi/|archive-date=January 30, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBefore deciding on CGI, the filmmakers had also considered depicting Rufus using puppets before ultimately determining that computer animation was \"the only way to capture his expressiveness ... We really worked hard with the animators to make him feel real, because we didn\u2019t want a [[Who Framed Roger Rabbit|''Roger Rabbit'']] situation going on where the world is live-action and then you have this cartoon character. We wanted Rufus to be part of their world and grounded, even though he is expressive, cute and fun.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> The visual effects studio [[Pixomondo]] was responsible for animating Rufus, a task they found challenging because, according to director [[Zach Lipovsky]], the animals \"are pretty disgusting creatures\", finding it \"hilarious to have one of the grossest animals be the [show and film's] comedic relief.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Because the computer-animated character needed to be more realistic than his cuter, stylized [[Traditional animation|traditionally animated]] counterpart, the Pixomondo artists worked for several months to determine a suitable \"balance between cute and real\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe character's origins and his relationship with Ron are altered for the film, in which Ron discovers Rufus in a science lab.<ref name=\":6\" /> Giambrone explained, \"Ron knew that that [Rufus] was like a missing part of him ... Then we get to see how they help each other out for the rest of the movie\".<ref name=\":6\" /> The actors did not see Rufus's final design until the character's visual effects were completely rendered, instead looking at either Giambrone's shoulder or a figurine that they found hardly resembled Rufus while filming.<ref name=\":10\" /> Giambrone was pleased with the character's design upon seeing it for the first time, expounding, \"I knew that was exactly what he should look like and it just felt like I was reunited with a buddy, seeing the movie with Rufus in it.\u201d<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n== Reception and impact ==\n''[[The New York Times]]'' television critic [[Julie Salamon]] wrote that \"the cheerful presence of Rufus ... signals that the show's executive producer and director, [[Chris Bailey (animator)|Chris Bailey]], doesn't mind getting cute in obvious ways.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/07/movies/tv-weekend-a-superhero-as-retro-as-she-s-cool.html|title=TV Weekend; A Superhero As Retro As She's Cool|last=Salamon|first=Julie|authorlink=Julie Salamon|date=June 7, 2002|website=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131173456/https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/07/movies/tv-weekend-a-superhero-as-retro-as-she-s-cool.html|archive-date=January 31, 2020|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]''<nowiki/>'s Alex Kane cited Rufus among the show's \"charming cast\" of memorable characters,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/reviewedcom/2019/11/12/how-to-watch-kim-possible-disney-plus/2564136001/|title=How to watch Kim Possible|last=Kane|first=Alex|date=November 12, 2019|website=[[USA Today]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131173457/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/reviewedcom/2019/11/12/how-to-watch-kim-possible-disney-plus/2564136001/|archive-date=January 31, 2020|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> while the ''[[Post-Gazette|Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]''<nowiki/>'s [[Rob Owen (journalist)|Rob Owen]] identified Rufus as the show's [[breakout character]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/tv/20020607owen0607fnp3.asp|title=On the Tube: Animated 'Kim Possible' new brand of action hero|last=Owen|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Owen (journalist)|date=June 7, 2002|website=[[Post-Gazette]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513193625/http://old.post-gazette.com/tv/20020607owen0607fnp3.asp|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> Rufus is considered one of the show's most popular characters and components,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> establishing himself as a fan favorite.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/nancy-cartwright-returns-as-rufus-in-kim-possible/|title=Nancy Cartwright Returns as Rufus in \u2018Kim Possible\u2019|last=Milligan|first=Mercedes|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[Animation Magazine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129074217/https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/nancy-cartwright-returns-as-rufus-in-kim-possible/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://d23.com/kim-possibles-fan-fave-rufus-captain-marvel-posters-plus-news-briefs/|title=Rufus the Naked Mole-Rat is Back in Live-Action Kim Possible|last=Potter|first=Courtney|date=January 17, 2019|website=[[D23 (Disney)|D23]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129172808/https://d23.com/kim-possibles-fan-fave-rufus-captain-marvel-posters-plus-news-briefs/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> McCorkle believes Rufus is the series' most popular character among younger viewers,<ref name=\":0\" /> an observation with which Judith S. Gillies of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' agreed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/tv/2002/06/16/kim-possible-leads-summers-fresh-fare/37a0ad3f-9eb7-4632-8565-8e952e7ef2e4/|title='Kim Possible' Leads Summer's Fresh Fare|last=Gillies|first=Judith S.|date=June 16, 2002|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref> Dylan Kickham of ''[[Elite Daily]]'' named Rufus both \"iconic\" and \"Everyone's favorite naked mole-rat\".<ref name=\":9\" /> Similarly, the ''[[Rockford Register Star]]'' called Rufus \"our favorite naked mole-rat\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rrstar.com/entertainment/20180811/holy-naked-mole-rat-kim-possible-live-action-movie-is-going-meta|title=Holy Naked Mole Rat! The Kim Possible Live-Action Movie Is Going Meta|last=|first=|date=August 11, 2018|website=[[Rockford Register Star]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Andy Swift of ''[[TVLine]]'' deemed Rufus an \"iconic\" character.<ref name=\":8\" /> Furthermore, Kickham believes Rufus' role in the series is \"the reason why so many young adults have actually heard of naked mole-rats.\"<ref name=\":9\" /> Cartwright's performance earned her a [[Daytime Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Performer in an Animated Program|Outstanding Performer in an Animated Program]] at the [[31st Daytime Emmy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/daytime-emmy-noms-unveiled/|title=Daytime Emmy Noms Unveiled|last=Ball|first=Ryan|date=March 4, 2004|website=[[Animation Magazine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130160935/https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/daytime-emmy-noms-unveiled/|archive-date=January 30, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/news/duck-dodgers-leads-daytime-emmy-nominations|title=Duck Dodgers Leads Daytime Emmy Nominations|last=Baisley|first=Sarah|date=March 4, 2004|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130161207/https://www.awn.com/news/duck-dodgers-leads-daytime-emmy-nominations|archive-date=January 30, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> [[MovieWeb]]'s Jeremy Dick hailed Rufus as \"one of Cartwright's best roles\".<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nFans of the series were initially outraged when the film adaptation's first trailer did not feature Rufus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/movies/2018/12/07/kim-possible-live-action-movie-trailer-rufus-naked-mole-rat/#1|title='Kim Possible' Fans in Uproar Over No Naked Mole Rat in Live-Action Trailer|last=Outlaw|first=Kofi|date=December 7, 2018|website=Comic Book|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129074254/https://comicbook.com/movies/2018/12/07/kim-possible-live-action-movie-trailer-rufus-naked-mole-rat/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Fans were eventually delighted to learn that Cartwright would be reprising her role in the film.<ref name=\":11\" /> While Blair Marnell of [[Nerdist News|Nerdist]] opined that producers should be open to recasting the film's main characters in favor of more diverse actors, she insisted that \"As long as Nancy Cartwright wants to reprise her role as the voice of Rufus, she should be able to do that for life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.nerdist.com/kim-possible-live-action-tv-movie-disney/|title=Kim Possible's Coming Back As a Live-action TV Movie|last=Marnelll|first=Blair|date=February 7, 2018|website=[[Nerdist News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref> Reviewing the film, [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'s Petrana Radulovic described Rufus as \"just silly enough as to not be jarring.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/tv/2019/2/15/18226603/kim-possible-live-action-movie-review|title=Kim Possible deserves a place among DCOM classics|last=Radulovic|first=Petrana|date=February 15, 2019|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Despite being disappointed with the overall film and Rufus' comparative lack of screentime, Aydan Rossovich of ''The Bear River Current'' felt he was \"The only acceptable character ... while it\u2019s disappointing that he was barely in it, if he had been in the movie more than he was, it would have just made it even more annoying.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brcurrent.com/index.php/2019/03/13/review-disneys-kim-possible-movie-disappoints-childhood-fans/|title=Review: Disney\u2019s \"Kim Possible\" movie disappoints childhood fans|last=Rossovich|first=Aydan|date=March 13, 2019|website=The Bear River Current|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] Jobs crowned Rufus \"one of the most faithful, yet smallest sidekicks of all time.\"<ref name=\":14\" /> Rufus has been called the most famous naked mole-rat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tulsazoo.org/naked-mole-rat-pups-born-at-the-tulsa-zoo/|title=Naked Mole Rat Pups Born at the Tulsa Zoo|last=|first=|date=|website=The Tulsa Zoo|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129161909/https://tulsazoo.org/naked-mole-rat-pups-born-at-the-tulsa-zoo/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020|quote=The most famous naked mole rat is the fictional Rufus character from Kim Possible.}}</ref> Kristy Pirone of ''[[Screen Rant]]'' believes Rufus \"will live in perpetuity as the most famous naked mole-rat of all time.\"<ref name=\":12\" /> Massive Science credits Rufus and ''Kim Possible'' with introducing naked mole-rats into mainstream popular culture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://massivesci.com/articles/naked-mole-rats-aging-cancer/|title=Do naked mole rats hold the answers to cancer prevention and aging?|last=Shepard|first=Alyssa|date=June 28, 2018|website=Massive Science|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129174520/https://massivesci.com/articles/naked-mole-rats-aging-cancer/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> The [[Liberty Science Center]] observed that most people may \"only know about naked mole rats via cartoon characters\", such as Rufus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lsc.org/news-and-social/news/naked-mole-rats-have-arrived-at-liberty-science-center|title=Naked mole rats have arrived at Liberty Science Center|last=|first=|date=January 11, 2017|website=[[Liberty Science Center]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204171700/https://lsc.org/news-and-social/news/naked-mole-rats-have-arrived-at-liberty-science-center|archive-date=February 4, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> The [[Field Museum of Natural History]] wrote that \"Rufus stole the hearts of all who watched him save the day. In many episodes, Rufus is the hero, and like Kim and Ron, scientists agree that naked mole-rats are pretty cool.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fieldmuseum.org/blog/naked-mole-rats-not-mole-not-rat-and-not-african-mole-rat|title=Naked mole-rats: Not a mole, not a rat, and not an African mole-rat|last=Gaare|first=Megan|date=December 1, 2014|website=[[Field Museum of Natural History]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195036/https://www.fieldmuseum.org/blog/naked-mole-rats-not-mole-not-rat-and-not-african-mole-rat|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{KimPossible|state=expanded}}\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2002]]\n[[Category:Fictional rodents]]\n[[Category:Television sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Anthropomorphic animal characters]]\n[[Category:Anthropomorphic rodents]]\n", "name_user": "Horseradishy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rufus_(Kim_Possible)"}
{"title_page": "2020 Easter tornado outbreak", "text_new": "{{pp-move|reason=Persistent [[WP:Vandalism|vandalism]]|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Tornado outbreak in southeast US}}\n\n{{current tornado outbreak|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = Tornado outbreak of April 12\u201313, 2020\n| image = April 12\u201313, 2020 tornado outbreak warnings and reports.png\n| alt = Map plotting locations of tornado touchdowns and tornado warning polygons across the Southeastern United States\n| caption = Map of tornado warnings and confirmed tornadoes from the outbreak\n| type = Tornado outbreak\n| active = April 12\u201313, 2020\n| lowest temperature = \n| tornadoes = 77+\n| fujitascale = EF4\n| enhanced = yes\n| tornado duration = \n| highest winds = {{convert|170\u2013205|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} <small>(Estimated by SPC)</small><ref name=\"SPC MD 360\">{{Cite web |author=Nick Nauslar |author2=John Hart |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0360.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 360 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref>\n| hail = \n| gusts = \n| maximum snow = \n| power outages = 1.3 million\n| total fatalities = 34 fatalities (plus 4 non-tornadic)\n| damages = \n| affected = [[Southeastern United States]]\n| current advisories = \n| partof = the '''[[Tornadoes of 2020|tornado outbreaks of 2020]]'''\n}}\n\nA series of destructive [[tornado]]es affected the Southeastern United States on [[Easter]] Sunday and Monday, April 12\u201313, 2020. Several were responsible for prompting [[tornado emergency|tornado emergencies]], including the first one to be issued by the [[National Weather Service]] in Charleston, South Carolina. A large [[squall line]] formed and tracked through the [[Mid-Atlantic (United States)|mid-Atlantic]] on April 13, prompting multiple tornado warnings and [[Tornado watch|watches]]. Fifteen total watches were produced during the course of the event, two of which were designated [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]]s. With 34 tornadic fatalities reported, it was the deadliest tornado outbreak in the U.S. since the [[tornado outbreak of April 27\u201330, 2014|April 2014 tornado outbreak]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/04/13/tornadoes-severe-weather-south-brutal-storms-moving-into-east/2981106001/ |title=Tornado outbreak in the South leaves at least 30 dead |first=Susan Miller and Doyle |last=Rice |website=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\n==Meteorological synopsis==\n[[File:Southeast_US_severe_weather_outbreak_2020-04-12_2156z.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Satellite image of the [[extratropical cyclone]] responsible for the outbreak across the Southeastern United States at 21:56&nbsp;UTC on April&nbsp;12]]\nFor weeks throughout March and into April, an expansive [[Ridge (meteorology)|area of high pressure]] built across the Southeast United States,<ref name=\"twc\">{{Cite web |url=https://weather.com/forecast/regional/news/2020-03-23-record-heat-hot-temperatures-south-late-march |title=Summerlike Heat Will Set Record-High Temperatures in Parts of the South Into This Weekend |publisher=The Weather Channel |date=March 23, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> contributing to abnormally warm temperatures across much of the country. The United States as a whole experienced its seventeenth warmest March, continuing the pattern that persisted throughout winter. In particular, many locations along the U.S. and Mexican Gulf coasts saw record warmest temperatures for the month.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Bob Henson |url=https://www.wunderground.com/cat6/us-stays-on-a-warm-mostly-wet-track-in-march |title=U.S. Stays on a Warm, Mostly Wet Track in March |publisher=Weather Underground |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Calm weather associated with the high-pressure area induced rapid warming of the Gulf of Mexico waters to their highest values in the modern record\u2014greater than {{convert|2|C-change|abbr=on}} above the 1971\u20132010 average\u2014as well as a moistening of the air near the surface.<ref name=\"twc\" /><ref>{{Cite web |author=Bob Henson |url=https://www.wunderground.com/cat6/severe-outbreak-to-rip-from-texas-to-mid-atlantic-sunday-into-monday |title=Severe Outbreak to Rip from Texas to Mid-Atlantic Sunday into Monday |publisher=Weather Underground |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Increased instability associated with anomalously warm and moist air from the Gulf of Mexico has been associated with an increased risk of severe weather and tornado activity.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/weather/2020/03/31/gulf-of-mexico-warm-tornadoes-hurricanes/ |title=Abnormally warm Gulf of Mexico could intensify the upcoming tornado and hurricane seasons |author=Matthew Cappucci |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first indications of organized severe weather came on April&nbsp;8, when the [[Storm Prediction Center]] (SPC) outlined 15% probabilities for severe weather within {{convert|25|mi|km|abbr=on}} of a point from central Texas eastward into the [[Florida Panhandle]] and eastern Georgia valid for April 11\u201312.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Andy Dean |author2=Greg Dial |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/exper/day4-8/archive/2020/day4-8_20200408.html |title=Day 4-8 Severe Weather Outlook Issued on Apr 8, 2020 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> These threat areas were later refined with the introduction of a day-3 [[Storm Prediction Center#Categories|moderate risk]], the fourth of five threat levels, across northeastern Louisiana through central Alabama on April&nbsp;10.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Andy Dean |author2=Greg Dial |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day3otlk_20200410_0730.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Apr 10, 2020 0730 UTC Day 3 Severe Thunderstorm Outlook |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> Historically, the SPC issues one day-3 moderate risk every year, and half of those over the previous decade were later upgraded to High risk, the highest threat level.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/weather/2020/04/10/severe-weather-outbreak-likely-deep-south-during-easter-weekend/ |title=Severe weather likely in South on Easter weekend, including powerful tornadoes |author=Matthew Cappucci |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=April 10, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Over subsequent days, a significant mid-level [[Shortwave (meteorology)|shortwave trough]] progressed eastward across the United States. By the pre-dawn hours of April&nbsp;12, mid-level cooling associated with the feature overspread the [[Edwards Plateau]], [[Texas Hill Country|Hill Country]], and much of central Texas. Accordingly, an intense line of severe thunderstorms developed along a [[dry line]] while vigorous [[Atmospheric convection|convective]] development formed farther east.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Brynn Kerr |author2=Rich Thompson |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0345.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 345 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> These thunderstorms were initially isolated in nature but soon coalesced into a [[mesoscale convective system]] as they encountered an enhanced corridor of warm air streaming northward, as well as very strong [[wind shear]].<ref>{{Cite web |author=Brynn Kerr |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0346.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 346 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author=Brynn Kerr |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0348.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 348 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> This [[storm complex]] progressed across northern Louisiana through the late morning and early afternoon hours, contributing to multiple [[Tornado debris signature|tornado debris signatures]].<ref>{{Cite web |author=Aaron Gleason |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0351.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 351 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> One such tornado in [[Monroe, Louisiana|Monroe]] was rated EF3 strength.<ref name=\"SHV0412\" /> In advance of the line, a lifting [[warm front]] aided in the formation of a very moist, highly unstable, and highly sheared environment across and northeastern Louisiana and much of Mississippi.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Aaron Gleason |author2=Jeremy Grams |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0350.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 350 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> Accordingly, the SPC issued a [[particularly dangerous situation]] tornado watch into the late evening hours.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Jeremy Grams |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2020/ww0106.html |title=Storm Prediction Center PDS Tornado Watch 106 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref>\n\n[[File:April 13, 2020, Livingston, South Carolina EF3 tornado damage.jpg|thumb|right|Severe damage to a grove of trees near [[Livingston, South Carolina]], from an EF3 tornado on the morning of April&nbsp;13.]]\nA [[weather balloon]] launch from [[Jackson, Mississippi]], at 18:00&nbsp;UTC revealed the presence of a [[capping inversion]] across the region. This cap was expected to weaken across central Mississippi,<ref>{{Cite web |author=Aaron Gleason |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0357.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 357 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> while forecasters expressed more uncertainty about its longevity across southern Mississippi and Louisiana.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Jeremy Grams |author2=Aaron Gleason |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0353.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 353 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> As a small [[Low-pressure area|area of low pressure]] progressed across northwestern Mississippi, it caused surface winds to turn out of the east-southeast, enhancing the potential for tornadoes. As a cluster of storms across central Mississippi progressed toward the northeast, it began to intensify and develop [[supercell]] characteristics with an attendant threat of strong tornadoes.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Aaron Gleason |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0355.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 355 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> Farther south, two distinct supercells developed within an environment where long-tracked, significant tornadoes were favored, both exhibiting extremely strong rotation and distinct debris signatures.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Nick Nauslar |author2=John Hart |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0362.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 362 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> Based on previous storm structures in similar environments, the SPC remarked that \"this is an exceptionally rare event\" and estimated tornadic winds of {{convert|170|\u2013|205|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, consistent with a tornado of [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF4 or EF5 intensity]].<ref name=\"SPC MD 360\" /><ref>{{Cite web |author=Steve Goss |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0368.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 368 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author=Steve Goss |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0369.html |title=Storm Prediction Center Mesoscale Discussion 369 |publisher=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> After conducting damage surveys, meteorologists identified two intense tornadoes with the first supercell, one of EF3 intensity that killed three people northwest of Salem to southwest of [[Bassfield, Mississippi|Bassfield]] and an even stronger one of EF4 intensity from south of Bassfield to southwest of [[Pachuta, Mississippi|Pachuta]].<ref name=\"ef3walthall\" /><ref name=\"ef4bassfield\" /> An EF3 tornado was identified with the second supercell.<ref name=\"ef3lawrence\" />\n\nThroughout the evening hours, the severe weather and tornado risk shifted eastward into Alabama, with a comma-head circulation across northern Alabama contributing to multiple confirmed tornadoes.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Goss|title=Mesoscale Discussion Number 363|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0363.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 12, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> This feature continued into northwestern Georgia, maintaining its well-defined structure in spite of a marginally unstable environment.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Goss|title=Mesoscale Discussion Number 369|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0369.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 12, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado carved a path from northwest of [[Chatsworth, Georgia|Chatsworth, Georgia]] to southeast of [[Benton, Tennessee]], killing seven people. While local enhancement of storm activity occurred within an extensive line of convection in central Alabama,<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Goss|title=Mesoscale Discussion Number 371|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0371.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 12, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> dewpoints rose in the wake of the earlier storm complex across northern Georgia and southeastern Tennessee, further boosting instability values in the presence of extremely strong wind shear.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Goss|title=Mesoscale Discussion Number 373|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0373.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 12, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> An EF3 tornado killed two people in the outskirts of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"tn\" /> The pre-frontal squall line shifted eastward into eastern Georgia and the Carolinas overnight. An EF3 tornado was confirmed south of [[Thomaston, Georgia|Thomaston]] to northwest of Redbone in Georgia.<ref name=\"FFC_0413\" /> A second EF3 tornado from south-southeast of [[Westminster, South Carolina|Westminster]] to west of [[Central, South Carolina|Central]] in South Carolina killed one person.<ref name=\"ef3westminster\" /> Yet another EF3 from east-northeast of [[Elko, South Carolina|Elko]] to west-southwest of [[St. Matthews, South Carolina|St. Matthews]] in South Carolina caused two more fatalities.<ref name=\"livingston\" /> For the 24-hour period ending 12:00&nbsp;UTC April&nbsp;13, the National Weather Service issued 141 tornado warnings, the most in one day since the [[tornado outbreak of March 2\u20133, 2012]].<ref>{{cite tweet|author=Daryl Herzmann|user=akrherz|title=My unofficial data has 141 Tornado Warnings issued by the @NWS for the 12z to 12z (7 AM CDT) period ending this morning (13 April 2020).  This is the largest number of warnings since 285 on 2-3 March 2012.  27-28 Apr 2011 is largest on record at 450.|number=1249672288435396609|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Through the morning hours of April&nbsp;13, the line of intense thunderstorms continued eastward and intensified given marginal daytime heating, a steady stream of rich moisture, and intense low-level wind shear.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brynn Kerr|title=Mesoscale Discussion Number 379|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/md0379.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> The SPC had already outlined an Enhanced risk of severe weather along the U.S. East Coast from southeastern Georgia northward into northern Virginia.<ref>{{cite web|author=Elizabeth Leitman|title=Apr 13, 2020 0600 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day1otlk_20200413_1200.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Swaths of damaging winds and tornadoes were recorded throughout the day, including 12 tornadoes in North Carolina, the sixth largest one-day outbreak on record in the state going back to 1950.<ref>{{cite tweet|author=Kathie Dello|user=KathieDello|title=It ranks as the 6th most number of confirmed tornadoes in 1 day in North Carolina, dating back to 1950 (s/o to Tim for asking the q)|number=1250186786371964928|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Confirmed tornadoes==\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 77+\n|FU = 0\n|F0 = 21\n|F1 = 32\n|F2 = 14\n|F3 = 9\n|F4 = 1\n|F5 = 0\n|Enhanced=yes\n}}\n\n===April 12 event===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|+ List of confirmed tornadoes \u2013 Sunday, April 12, 2020{{efn|All dates are based on the local [[time zone]] where the tornado touched down; however, all times are in [[Coordinated Universal Time]] for consistency.|group=note|name=Date/Time}}\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:3%; text-align:center;\"|[[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF#]]\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:7%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|Location\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|County / Parish\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:5%; text-align:center;\"|State\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Start Coord.\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Time ([[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]])\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Path length\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Max width\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:48%; text-align:center;\"|Summary\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:3%; text-align:center;\"|Refs\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{storm colour|cat1}}\" | EF1\n|NNW of [[Melvin, Texas|Melvin]]\n|[[McCulloch County, Texas|McCulloch]]\n|[[Texas|TX]]\n|{{Coord|31.2145|-99.5846 |name=Melvin (Apr. 12, EF1)}}\n|09:05\u201309:13\n|{{convert|5.2|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|300|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|A tornado snapped or uprooted multiple oak trees and killed one calf.\n|<ref>{{cite web |agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Offi