ivation of KOI8-R with only the letter subset implemented)\n*[[KOI character encodings]]\n*[[RELCOM]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"IBM\">{{cite web |title=SBCS code page information - CPGID: 00878 / Name: Russian internet koi8-r |work=IBM Software: Globalization: Coded character sets and related resources: Code pages by CPGID: Code page identifiers. |publisher=[[IBM]] |id=C-H 3-3220-050 |url=https://www-01.ibm.com/software/globalization/cp/cp00878.html |access-date=2017-02-18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218113007/https://www-01.ibm.com/software/globalization/cp/cp00878.html |archive-date=2017-02-18}} [ftp://ftp.software.ibm.com/software/globalization/gcoc/attachments/CP00878.pdf] [ftp://ftp.software.ibm.com/software/globalization/gcoc/attachments/CP00878.txt]</ref>\n<ref name=\"IBM_878\">{{cite web |title=CCSID information document; CCSID 878; KOI8-R CYRILLIC |publisher=[[IBM]] |url=https://www-01.ibm.com/software/globalization/ccsid/ccsid878.html |access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Unicode_2016_KOI8-R\">{{cite web |author-first=Helmut |author-last=Richter |orig-year=1999-08-18 |date=2016-01-04 |version=2.0 |title=KOI8-R.TXT |url=ftp://ftp.unicode.org/Public/MAPPINGS/VENDORS/MISC/KOI8-R.TXT |access-date=2016-12-09 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*<!-- <ref name=\"Flohr_2016_KOI8-R\"> -->{{cite web |title=Locale::RecodeData::KOI8_R - Conversion routines for KOI8-R |author-first1=Guido |author-last1=Flohr |author-first2=Gabor |author-last2=Kiss |author-first3=Andrey A. |author-last3=Chernov |version=1.0 |work=[[CPAN]] libintl-perl |date=2016 |orig-year=2006<!-- 2002 --> |url=http://search.cpan.org/~guido/libintl-perl/lib/Locale/RecodeData/KOI8_R.pm |access-date=2017-01-15 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115040202/http://search.cpan.org/~guido/libintl-perl/lib/Locale/RecodeData/KOI8_R.pm |archive-date=2017-01-15}}<!-- </ref> -->\n* {{cite web |title=koi8-r (Russian U*IX encoding, also used by RELCOM) |version=1.20 |author-first=Kosta |author-last=Kostis |url=http://www.kostis.net/charsets/koi8-r.htm |access-date=2017-01-16 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116141106/http://www.kostis.net/charsets/koi8-r.htm |archive-date=2017-01-16}}\n* RFC 1489\n* {{cite web |title=KOI8-R (RFC 1489) |work=[[Kermit (protocol)|Kermit]] |publisher=[[Columbia University]] |url=ftp://kermit.columbia.edu/kermit/charsets/koi8r.txt |access-date=2017-02-18 |url-status=live}}\n* {{cite web |title=CYRILLIC ENCODING FAQ Version 1.3 |version=1.3 |date=1993-03-13 |author-first1=Andras |author-last1=Kornai |author-first2=David J. |author-last2=Birnbaum |author-first3=Frank |author-last3=da Cruz\n|author-first4=Bur |author-last4=Davis\n|author-first5=George |author-last5=Fowler\n|author-first6=Richard B. |author-last6=Paine\n|author-first7=Slava |author-last7=Paperno\n|author-first8=Keld J. |author-last8=Simonsen\n|author-first9=Glenn E. |author-last9=Thobe\n|author-first10=Dimitri |author-last10=Vulis\n|author-first11=Johan W. |author-last11=van Wingen |url=ftp://kermit.columbia.edu/kermit/charsets/cyrillic-summary.txt |access-date=2017-02-18 |url-status=live<!-- |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218142454/http://www.verycomputer.com/42_17e2e72303d2c08b_1.htm -->}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://2cyr.com/decode/ Universal Cyrillic decoder], an online program that may help recovering [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] texts with broken KOI8-R or other [[character encoding]]s.\n*<!-- <ref name=\"KOI8\">-->{{cite web |title=The Home of the KOI8-R since 1995 |orig-year=1995 |url=http://koi8.pp.ru/main.html |access-date=2016-12-05 |url-status=live}}<!-- </ref> -->\n*<!-- <ref name=\"Czyborra_1998_Cyrillic\"> -->{{cite web |title=The Cyrillic Charset Soup |url=http://czyborra.com/charsets/cyrillic.html |access-date=2016-12-03 |author-first=Roman |author-last=Czyborra |orig-year=1998-05-25 |date=1998-11-30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203230933/http://czyborra.com/charsets/cyrillic.html |archive-date=2016-12-03}}<!-- </ref> -->\n*<!-- <ref name=\"Hohlov\"> -->{{cite web |author-first=Yu. E. |author-last=Hohlov |title=Cyrillic Information Representation in Electronic Form - Character Set (Code Page) Tables |url=http://www.iis.ru/cyrillic/resource/tables.en.html |access-date=2016-12-05 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205140054/http://www.iis.ru/cyrillic/resource/tables.en.html |archive-date=2016-12-05}}<!-- </ref> -->\n*<!-- <ref name=\"Nechayev_2013_8-Bit-Cyrillic\"> -->{{cite web |title=Review of 8-bit Cyrillic encodings universe |author-first=Valentin |author-last=Nechayev |date=2013 |orig-year=2001 |url=http://segfault.kiev.ua/cyrillic-encodings/ |access-date=2016-12-05 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205134629/http://segfault.kiev.ua/cyrillic-encodings/ |archive-date=2016-12-05}}<!-- </ref> -->\n\n{{Cyrillic encodings}}\n{{Character encoding}}\n\n[[Category:Character sets]]\n[[Category:Computing in the Soviet Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox character encoding\n|name=KOI8-R\n|lang=[[Russian language|Russian]], [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]\n|classification=8-bit [[KOI character encodings|KOI]], [[extended ASCII]]\n|basedon=[[KOI-8]]\n|extends=[[KOI8-B]]\n|otherrelated=[[KOI8-U]], [[KOI8-RU]]\n}}\n'''KOI8-R''' (RFC 1489) is an 8-bit [[character encoding]], designed to cover [[Russian language|Russian]], which uses a [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] alphabet. It also happens to cover [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]], but has not been used for that purpose since [[CP1251]] was accepted. A derivative encoding is [[KOI8-U]], which adds [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] characters. The original [[KOI-8]] encoding was designed by Soviet authorities in 1974. \nKOI8 remains much more commonly used than [[ISO 8859-5]], which never really caught on. Another common Cyrillic character encoding is [[Windows-1251]]. The use of these older code pages is being replaced with [[Unicode]] as a more common way to represent Cyrillic together with other languages.\n\nIn [[Microsoft Windows]], KOI8-R is assigned the code page number 20866. In [[IBM]], KOI8-R is assigned code page 878.<ref name=\"IBM\"/><ref name=\"IBM_878\"/>\n\nKOI8 stands for ''Kod Obmena Informatsiey, 8 bit'' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0434 \u041e\u0431\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0418\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0435\u0439, 8 \u0431\u0438\u0442}}) which means \"Code for Information Exchange, 8 bit\".\n\nThe KOI8 character sets have the property that the Russian Cyrillic letters are in pseudo-Roman order rather than the normal Cyrillic alphabetical order as in ISO 8859-5 or Unicode. Although this may seem unnatural, it has the useful property that if the 8th bit is stripped, the text is partially readable in ASCII and may convert to syntactically correct [[KOI7]]. For instance, \"\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0422\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0442\" in KOI8-R becomes ''rUSSKIJ tEKST'' (\"Russian Text\") if the 8th bit is stripped; attempting to interpret the ASCII string ''rUSSKIJ tEKST'' as KOI7 yields \"\u0420\u0423\u0421\u0421\u041a\u0418\u0419 \u0422\u0415\u041a\u0421\u0422\". KOI8 was based on [[Russian Morse code]], which was created from Latin [[Morse code]] based on sound similarities, and which has the same connection to the Latin Morse codes for A-Z as KOI8 has with [[ASCII]].\n\n==Character set==\nThe following table shows the KOI8-R encoding.<ref name=\"IBM\"/><ref name=\"Unicode_2016_KOI8-R\"/> Each character is shown with its equivalent [[Unicode]] code point.\n\n{|{{chset-tableformat}}\n{{chset-table-header|KOI8-R}}\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|0_<br/>0}}\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|1_<br/>16}}\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|2_<br/>32}}\n|{{chset-color-misc}}|{{chset-ctrl|0020|[[space character|SP]]|32}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0021|[[Exclamation mark|!]]|33}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0022|[[Quotation mark|&#x22;]]|34}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0023|[[Number sign|#]]|35}}\n|{{chset-color-graph}}|{{chset-cell|0024|[[Dollar sign|$]]|36}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0025|[[Percent sign|%]]|37}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0026|[[Ampersand|&amp;]]|38}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0027|[[Apostrophe|&#x27;]]|39}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0028|[[Parenthesis|(]]|40}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0029|[[Parenthesis|)]]|41}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|002A|[[Asterisk|*]]|42}}\n|{{chset-color-graph}}|{{chset-cell|002B|[[Plus sign|+]]|43}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|002C|[[Comma (punctuation)|,]]|44}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|002D|[[Hyphen-minus|-]]|45}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|002E|[[Full stop|.]]|46}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|002F|[[Slash (punctuation)|/]]|47}}\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|3_<br/>48}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0030|[[0]]|48}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0031|[[1]]|49}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0032|[[2]]|50}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0033|[[3]]|51}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cel